# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: netherlands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The **1968 Tour de France** was the 55th edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] It took place between 27 June and 21 July, with 22 stages covering a distance of 4,492 km (2,791 mi).
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Eleven national teams of 10 riders competed, with three French teams, two Belgian teams and one from Germany, Spain, the United Kingdom, Italy, the Netherlands, and a combined Swiss/Luxembourgian team.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The 1968 Tour marked the first time the race would end at the Vélodrome de Vincennes, replacing the now-defunct Parc des Princes Velodrome which served as the final stop from 1904 to 1967.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The general classification was won by Jan Janssen, who overtook Herman Van Springel in the final time trial.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] After the death of Tom Simpson, doping controls had become mandatory.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] To further protect the cyclists, it was now allowed to get water during the race, and two rest days were added.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] To get more sponsor income, a new classification was added, the combination classification, calculated from the positions in the general, points and mountains classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The jersey of the points classification, which has been green in all other years, was red in 1968 for sponsorship reasons.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The 1968 Tour started with 110 cyclists, divided into 11 teams of 10 cyclists.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The route for the Tour de France was announced in December 1967.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] At that time, the last stage was not finalised yet, because the old finish place (the Parc des Princes) was no longer available, and a new one had to be found.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The 1968 Tour de France started on 27 June, and had two rest days, in Royan and Font-Romeu-Odeillo-Via.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was 2,408 m (7,900 ft) at the summit of the Port d'Envalira mountain pass on stage 13.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The initial time trial was won by Charly Grosskost, with most favourites shortly behind him.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Grosskost also won the next stage, and thus kept the lead.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the first part of the third stage, a team time trial, the Belgian A team won, and because of the time bonuses Herman Vanspringel took over the lead.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The next stages were all flat, and the favourites were unable to gain time on each other.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the fourth stage, a group without favourites escaped and won the stage with a margin of a few minutes; Jean-Pierre Genet was the best-placed cyclist of that group, and became the new leader.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] A similar thing happened in the first part of the fifth stage; Georges Vandenberghe was the only cyclist who had been present in both escape groups, and he became the new leader of the general classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Vandenberghe was now a few minutes ahead in the general classification, and kept that lead until the start of the Pyrenees after stage eleven.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Vandenberghe was expected to lose the lead in the twelfth stage, because he was not known to be a good climber.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] But he surprised, and stayed with some of the favourites, keeping the lead.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In that stage, the Dutch team was reduced to four cyclists, and the leader Jan Janssen did not look strong.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] On the other hand, the leader of the French team Raymond Poulidor had gained time, and seemed to be the best-placed favourite, in fifth place in the general classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the thirteenth stage, Vandenberghe again was able to stay at the front.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the last day in the Pyrenees during stage fourteen, Janssen won the stage, but won little time by that, as almost all cyclists were in the group just behind him.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the fifteenth stage, Raymond Poulidor was hit by a motor, but was able to remount and reach the finish, although he lost more than a minute on his direct competitors.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the sixteenth stage, French internal rivalry was dominating; while Roger Pingeon of the France A team was slowing down to drink, Lucien Aimar of the France B team attacked, and took a group of favourites with him.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Although Aimar was later dropped from that group, Godefroot, Janssen, Vanspringel, Bracke and Gandarias stayed at the front, while Pingeon, Poulidor and Vandenberghe lost more than nine minutes, and were out of contention.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The new leader was now Rolf Wolfshohl, with San Miguel in second place and Franco Bitossi in third place.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the eighteenth stage, Pingeon fought back and escaped early in the stage.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] He was joined by Bitossi, who was keen on taking over the lead in the general classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] On the last climb, Bitossi was out of energy and lost considerable time.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Pingeon won the stage, and San Miguel climbed up to the first place in the general classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] However, the top eight was within two minutes of each other.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the nineteenth stage, San Miguel lost a little time on Vanspringel, who became the new leader.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The next few stages did not change anything in the top of the general classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The Tour ended with a time trial, and before the time trial, Herman Van Springel was leading, followed by San Miguel at 12 seconds, Janssen at 16 seconds and Bitossi at 58 seconds.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Janssen won the final time trial, with Van Springel in second place, but the margin was large enough for Janssen to win the Tour.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Doping controls were performed daily on the first three riders to complete the stage and three more riders by random drawing.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Gimondi advised the Tour de France organizers adopt the aforementioned system, which was used at the Giro d'Italia earlier that year, in order for him to agree to participate in the race.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In total, 163 doping tests were performed.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Both were removed from the race, suspended for one month and given a fine.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] There were several classifications in the 1968 Tour de France, two of them awarding jerseys to their leaders.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The most important was the general classification, calculated by adding each cyclist's finishing times on each stage.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey; the winner of this classification is considered the winner of the Tour.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Additionally, there was a points classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In the points classification, cyclists got points for finishing among the best in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The jersey for the points classification leader was red in 1968, unlike all other years since its introduction in 1953, when it was green.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] There was also a mountains classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The organisation had categorised some climbs as either first, second, third, or fourth-category; points for this classification were won by the first cyclists that reached the top of these climbs first, with more points available for the higher-categorised climbs.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The leader of the mountains classification, which had been calculated since 1933 but had never had a jersey, also became identifiable by a "macaron" on his jersey.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] A newly introduced classification was the combination classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] This classification was calculated as a combination of the other classifications.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The leader was not identified by a jersey, but wore a "macaron" on their jersey.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The fifth individual classification was the intermediate sprints classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] This classification had similar rules as the points classification, but points were only awarded on intermediate sprints.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In 1968, this classification had no associated jersey.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] For the team classification, the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage were added; the leading team was the team with the lowest total time.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that led this classification wore yellow caps.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The Switzerland/Luxembourg team finished with only two cyclists.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each stage to the cyclist considered most combative.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The split stages each had a combined winner.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The decision was made by a jury composed of journalists who gave points.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points from votes in all stages led the combativity classification.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] Roger Pingeon won this classification, and was given overall the super-combativity award.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange was given in honour of Tour founder Henri Desgrange to the first rider to pass the summit of the Col des Aravis on stage 19.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] There was also the Souvenir Tom Simpson, given in honour of Tom Simpson, who died during the 1967 Tour.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] This prize was won by Roger Pingeon on stage 15 in the small town of Mirepoix.
[src:netherlands/1968-tour-de-france] It was the last edition in which the cyclists participated in national teams; from 1969 on, commercial teams were used.
[src:netherlands/1979-vuelta-a-espana] The 34th Edition ***Vuelta a España*** (Tour of Spain), a long-distance bicycle stage race and one of the three grand tours, was held from 24 April to 13 May 1979.
[src:netherlands/1979-vuelta-a-espana] It consisted of 19 stages covering a total of 3,373 km (2,096 mi), and was won by Joop Zoetemelk of the Miko–Mercier cycling team.
[src:netherlands/1979-vuelta-a-espana] Zoetemelk won two of the three ITT's and Fons De Wolf won the other.
[src:netherlands/1979-vuelta-a-espana] De Wolf also won the points classification as well as five stages, but Zoetemelk won the race with a comfortable lead ahead of Spanish climbing specialist Francisco Galdós and Michel Pollentier.
[src:netherlands/1979-vuelta-a-espana] Felipe Yáñez won the mountains classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The **1980 Tour de France** was the 67th edition of the Tour de France.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The total distance was 3,842 km (2,387 mi) over 22 stages.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In the first half of the race, Bernard Hinault started out strong by winning the prologue and two stages.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] However, knee problems forced Hinault to abandon the race while still in the lead.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Joop Zoetemelk became the new leader, and defended that position successfully.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Just as in 1979, when Hinault and Zoetemelk finished nearly a half hour ahead of the rest of the field, the 1980 edition was a battle between these two riders until Hinault abandoned.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] At the time Hinault was just 21 seconds ahead of Zoetemelk and the race was about to enter the Pyrenees.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk did not wear the yellow jersey during stage 13 though he did in every stage thereafter finishing the race with nearly a seven-minute advantage over second place Hennie Kuiper.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] It was his first Tour victory in his tenth attempt, after already having finished second in five editions.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The points classification was won by Rudy Pevenage, who also won the intermediate sprints classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The mountains classification was won by Raymond Martin, and Johan van der Velde won the young rider classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Two weeks before the Tour would start, there were only twelve teams interested in starting the Tour.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The teams with Italian and Spanish sponsors were focussed on the Giro d'Italia and the Vuelta a España, and thought their cyclists were not able to compete in two grand tours in one year.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] This prevented Giovanni Battaglin of the Spanish-based Inoxpran, the winner of the mountains classification of 1979, from defending his title.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Francesco Moser, who had left the 1980 Giro d'Italia injured, was the only Italian cyclist on the initial starting list, but he was not able to start, so the 1980 Tour was without Italian cyclists.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] One more team was added to the starting list, so the Tour 1980 started with thirteen teams, each with ten cyclists.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The Boston–Mavic–Amis du Tour team was a combination of the Belgian Boston–Mavic team and French cyclists without a contract, combined into the "Amis du Tour" team.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The three most important favourites for the victory were Bernard Hinault, Joop Zoetemelk and Hennie Kuiper.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Hinault was the winner of the two last editions, and had earlier that year won the 1980 Giro d'Italia.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk, the runner-up of the last two editions, had switched teams to the TI–Raleigh team, which was considered one of the strongest teams.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Kuiper had left the TI–Raleigh team and moved to the Peugeot team.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The manager of that team, Maurice De Muer, had already managed Bernard Thévenet to a Tour win, and this made Kuiper confident.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The 1980 Tour de France started on 26 June, and had two rest days, in Saint-Malo and Morzine.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was 2,642 m (8,668 ft) at the summit of the Col du Galibier mountain pass on stage 17.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Before the race, Hinault expressed dissatisfaction with the cobbled sections in stages five and six.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In the 1979 Tour, Hinault had lost time in these sections, and he considered to organise a strike.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Even though no strike was held, the route was still changed: after the fifth stage, tour organiser Félix Lévitan decided to change the first 20 kilometres (12 mi) of the stage, to avoid the worst cobbled sections.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The 25 stages were won by riders from only four countries.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In this year's edition of the Tour, the last rider in the general classification after the consecutives mountain stages (16-19) was eliminated.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The prologue was won by Hinault, who finished :05 ahead of Gerrie Knetemann and 0:23 ahead of the closest general classification rider Hennie Kuiper.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Stage 1A was a sprint finish won by Jan Raas and Stage 1B was the first Team Time Trial in which TI–Raleigh claimed the victory ahead of Renault and Peugeot gaining enough in the time bonus for Knetemann to become the new leader.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In Stage 2 Rudy Pevenage, Yvon Bertin and Pierre Bazzo escaped in a breakaway and were able to stay away the entire stage winning by nearly ten minutes over the rest of the field.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Pevenage claimed the stage victory with Bazzo taking second and while Bertin took third he was the highest placed of the three and took over the lead in the general classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Stage 3 was won by Henk Lubberding and Bertin ended up falling off the back losing considerable time, which made Pevenage the new overall leader going into the second individual time trial (ITT) in Stage 4.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Bernard Hinault was aiming to win his third straight Tour de France and in the ITT he looked to be well on his way dominating the rest of the field.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Of the 122 riders remaining in the main field only six of them were able to come within 2:00 of Hinault and nobody was able to finish within a minute of the defending champ.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Joop Zoetemelk was the closest to him taking second place at 1:16 back and in the overall situation overall Pevenage remained leader by about a minute over Bazzo with Hinault closing the gap to within six minutes.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Stage 5 was run in terrible weather, but the aggressive Hinault was looking to distance himself from the competition and went on the offensive together with Kuiper.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Hinault won the stage, with Kuiper finishing right on his wheel, gaining more than two minutes on all of the other of the general classification Riders although following this stage many riders began experiencing tendinitis problems, including Hinault.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Going into Stage 6 Hinault was within four minutes of Pevenage in the general classification and built a lead of more than 3:00 on Kuiper, nearly 4:00 on Zoetemelk and more than 5:00 on Raymond Martin and Joaquim Agostinho.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The stage was won by Jean-Louis Gauthier by a full second over the rest of the field with no major changes in the overall classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Stage 7A would prove to be the beginning of a remarkable run by the TI–Raleigh team, who won the team time trial (TTT) beginning a stretch where a rider from this team would win seven stages in a row.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The plan was working as Stage 7B was won by Jan Raas, Stage 8 by Bert Oosterbosch, Raas would win again in Stage 9 and Stage 10 was won by Cees Priem.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] After stage 10 Pevenage was still in Yellow by 2:44 over Bazzo with a 4:20 advantage over Hinault, however The Badger was in the lead among the serious contenders although his lead over Zoetemelk had been cut to 2:00 with Kuiper 2:24 behind Hinault.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Stage 11 was a time trial prior to going into the high mountains of the Pyrenees and if Hinault wanted to match the likes of Louison Bobet, Jacques Anquetil and Eddy Merckx by winning his third Tour de France in a row he would have to perform well.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The day however, belonged to Zoetemelk as he took the Stage victory with only eight riders finishing within 2:00 of him.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Finishing 0:46 behind was Hennie Kuiper with Agostinho coming in 3rd, Oosterbosch finishing 4th and Hinault in 5th 1:39 back.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Hinault was back in the yellow jersey but his lead over Zoetemelk was a minuscule 0:21.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Rudy Pevenage fell to 3rd place and Kuiper was 1:31 back with no other general classification (GC) contenders within 5:00.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Normally, Hinault was the better time trialist, so Zoetemelk's stage victory made him confident that he had the chance to win the Tour.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In Stage 12 Gerrie Knetemann and Ludo Peeters escaped and managed to beat the Peloton by more than a minute with Knetemann beating Peeters at the finish line.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Late that evening, with the first stage of the high mountains looming, Hinault decided to withdraw.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk, until that moment second in the general classification, became the new leader, but refused to don the yellow jersey during the following stage following the example of Eddy Merckx who refused to wear it in the 1971 Tour de France after Luis Ocaña left the race as leader.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In Stage 13, Zoetemelk rode in his notoriously conservative style, allowing Raymond Martin to escape, as he was a distant threat in the general classification, but he kept Kuiper close, who was now his main rival for the overall victory.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk would not stray from who he was as a rider and maintained this defensive tactic for the rest of the race.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Martin won the stage breaking the impressive streak of TI–Raleigh and climbing into 3rd place in the process.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Going into Stage 16 Zoetemelk was now 1:18 ahead of Kuiper and 5:03 ahead of his former teammate Martin.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In the 16th stage, one of Zoetemelk's present teammates Johan van der Velde, who had been riding a very good Tour, nearly fell off his bike and cut off Zoetemelk with van der Velde's back tire hitting Zoetemelk's front causing him to viciously crash into the pavement.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk quickly remounted and continued the race but was bleeding from his arm and thigh.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Jos De Schoenmaecker won the stage with the group of favourites coming in over a minute later as Zoetemelk was not only able to get back to the elite group, but he also put another 0:16 into Kuiper .
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The fall in the 16th stage did affect Zoetemelk's performance in stage 17, as Zoetemelk had to let others go on the first climb.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Helped by the Panzer Group, he was able to stay close to his competitors and was in good position for the final climb.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Mariano Martinez survived his breakaway attempt and won the stage as Zoetemelk was able to drop 2nd place Kuiper, who came partially unhinged losing almost 1:30.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] 3rd place Raymond Martin was able to leave Zoetemelk behind but it was near the end of the stage and by this point it was too little too late as he was only able to take 0:15 back.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In Stage 18 Ludo Loos escaped and crossed all five cols first, finishing more than five minutes ahead of the Peloton in a remarkable solo stage win which turned out to be the only Tour stage victory of his career.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk finished in the second group with Robert Alban and Lucien Van Impe nearly a minute ahead of Martin and 2:30 ahead of Kuiper who fell to 3rd place as Martin moved into 2nd.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] With the Alps now finished the last obstacle in the way of Zoetemelk winning his first Tour de France was the time trial in Stage 20.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Stage 19 was an Intermediate stage in which Sean Kelly and Ismael Lejarreta beat the Peloton to the line by 0:20 and Kelly earned his second career stage win by winning the sprint.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The overall situation remained the same going into the time trial which was won in dominating fashion by Joop Zoetemelk with only one rider coming within a minute of him and that rider was his own teammate Gerrie Knetemann.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] With Kuiper and Joaquim Agostinho finishing in 3rd and 4th at plus 1:12 and 1:13 respectively, Zoetemelk was now virtually assured of the overall victory with his lead now built to about 7:00 over Kuiper, who moved back into 2nd having a considerably better ride than Martin.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Stage 21 was a flat stage which was once again won by Sean Kelly and while Kelly rode an impressive Tour competing for the points classification, he ended up finishing second in that classification to Rudy Pevenage.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Between 1982 and 1989 Kelly would go on to win the points classification four times.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] On the final stage into Paris the blossoming star was in good position for the final sprint to go for another stage win, but he was beat to the line by Pol Verschuere, who won the first Tour stage of his career that afternoon on the Champs-Élysées.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk crossed in the middle of the pack side by side with teammate Gerrie Knetemann, who hoisted Zoetemelk's arm into the air while crossing the finish line.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] TI–Raleigh–Creda would win one of the Team Competitions and also claim an astonishing eleven stage wins, a feat which has not been repeated since.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Shortly before the start of the Tour, it was announced that Dietrich Thurau had tested positive in his national championship.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] He was allowed to start the Tour while his B-sample was being tested.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] His B-sample gave a negative result, so he could continue the Tour.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] On the day of the final time trial, when it was all but clear that Zoetemelk would be the winner, tour director Jacques Goddet wrote in the newspaper l'Équipe that the only thing that could keep Zoetemelk away from a Tour victory was the drug tests for anabolic products after the eighteenth stage.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] As the director, Goddet was well-informed about drug tests, and many journalists speculated that his comments meant that Zoetemelk's A-sample had returned positive.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk had tested positive in 1977, and was not happy about the insinuations.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Tour co-director Félix Lévitan apologised for Goddet's choice of words.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] At the end of the Tour, it was announced that all doping tests had returned negative.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] There were several classifications in the 1980 Tour de France, four of them awarding jerseys to their leaders.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In the 1979 Tour de France, Gerhard Schönbacher and Philippe Tesnière had both been trying to finish last, which had received attention from the press.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The Tour organisation wanted to the press to focus on the winners, so they added the rule that after the 14th to 20th stage, the last-ranked cyclist in the general classification would be removed.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Additionally, there was a points classification, where cyclists got points for finishing among the best in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification, and was identified with a green jersey.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The organisation had categorised some climbs as either *hors catégorie*, first, second, third, or fourth-category; points for this classification were won by the first cyclists that reached the top of these climbs first, with more points available for the higher-categorised climbs.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification, and wore a white jersey with red polka dots.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Another classification was the young rider classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] This was decided the same way as the general classification, but only cyclists younger than 24 were eligible, and the leader wore a white jersey.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] This classification had similar rules as the points classification, but only points were awarded on intermediate sprints.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In 1980, this classification had no associated jersey.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] A combination classification was also calculated; this was done by adding the points for the points classification, mountains classification, intermediate sprints classification and combativity award.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] A new competition was introduced in 1980, sponsored by the French television station TF1, therefore named "Grand Prix TF1".
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] It was calculated from the results in the other classifications, and therefore seen as a successor of the combination classification that was calculated from 1968 to 1974.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] There was no jersey associated with the Grand Prix TF1.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The Belgian Ludo Peeters won this classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that led this classification were identified by yellow caps.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] There was also a team points classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Cyclists received points according to their finishing position on each stage, with the first rider receiving one point.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The first three finishers of each team had their points combined, and the team with the fewest points led the classification.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The riders of the team leading this classification wore green caps.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each mass-start stage to the cyclist considered most combative.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Christian Levavasseur won this classification, and was given overall the super-combativity award.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange was given in honour of Tour founder Henri Desgrange to the first rider to pass the summit of the Col du Galibier on stage 17.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] After it was said that Zoetemelk only won because Hinault abandoned, Zoetemelk replied "Surely winning the Tour is a question of health and robustness?
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] If Hinault does not have that health and robustness and I have, that makes me a valid winner." Hinault agreed to that, saying that it was the absent rider (Hinault) who is at fault, not the one who replaces him.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] In the individual time trial prior to the start of the mountain stages Zoetemelk dominated Hinault to come within 21 seconds of the overall lead.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] While Hinault was rarely beaten in any individual time trial, it was common knowledge that Zoetemelk was probably the best mountain climber in the world and with the mountain stages about to begin it is unlikely Hinault's lead of 21 seconds would have held.
[src:netherlands/1980-tour-de-france] Hinault's knee problems were solved before the 1980 UCI Road World Championships, which he won.
[src:netherlands/bq] On 15 December 2010 the ISO 3166-1 code for Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba changed to reflect the BQ codified for the ccTLD.
[src:netherlands/bq] Previously, the Caribbean Netherlands used the former Netherlands Antilles's ccTLD, .an, which has been phased out in July 2015.
[src:netherlands/bq] As part of the Netherlands proper, .nl also applies.
[src:netherlands/bq] Use of the top level domain is as of July 2015 being considered and an economic evaluation is being performed to that effect.
[src:netherlands/bq] BQ was chosen as other possible codes had already been allocated.
[src:netherlands/eu] The .eu ccTLD was approved by ICANN on 22 March 2005 and put in the Internet root zone on 2 May 2005.
[src:netherlands/eu] Even though the EU is not a country (it is a sui generis intergovernmental and supranational organisation), it has an exceptional reservation in ISO 3166.
[src:netherlands/eu] The Commission and ICANN had extended negotiations lasting more than five years to secure its acceptance.
[src:netherlands/eu] The sunrise period was broken into two phases.
[src:netherlands/eu] The first phase, which began on 7 December 2005 was to facilitate applications by registrants with prior rights based on trademarks and geographic names.
[src:netherlands/eu] The second phase began on 7 February 2006 and covered company, trade and personal names.
[src:netherlands/eu] In the case of all Sunrise applications, the application needed to be accompanied by documents proving the claim to ownership of a certain right.
[src:netherlands/eu] The decision was then made by PricewaterhouseCoopers Belgium, which had been chosen as the validation agent by EURid.
[src:netherlands/eu] On 7 February 2006, the registry was opened for company, trade and personal names.
[src:netherlands/eu] In the first 15 minutes, there were 27,949 total applications, and after one hour, 71,235.
[src:netherlands/eu] On 7 April 2006 at 11 am CET registration became possible for non-trademark holders.
[src:netherlands/eu] Most people requesting domains had asked their registrars to put their requested domains in a queue, ensuring the best chance to register a domain.
[src:netherlands/eu] This way more than 700,000 domains were registered during the first 4 hours of operation.
[src:netherlands/eu] Some large registrars like GoDaddy and small registrars like Dotster suffered from long queues and unresponsiveness, allowing people to 'beat the queue' by registering through a registrar that had already processed its queue.
[src:netherlands/eu] By August 2006, 2 Million .eu domains had been registered.
[src:netherlands/eu] It was then fourth-largest ccTLD in Europe, after .de, .uk and .nl, and is one of the largest internationally.
[src:netherlands/eu] The number of .eu domain registrations during the year after the landrush 7 April 2006 to 6 April 2007 seems to have peaked at approximately 2.6 million .eu domains.
[src:netherlands/eu] The market adjustment that follows a landrush in any domain name extension ensures that the number of registered domains will fall as many speculative domain registrations that failed to be resold will not be renewed.
[src:netherlands/eu] This is sometimes referred to as the *Junk Dump*.
[src:netherlands/eu] On the morning of 7 April 2007, the number of active .eu domains stood at 2,590,160 with approximately 15,000 domains having been deleted since 5 April 2007.
[src:netherlands/eu] Approximately 1.5 million .eu domains were up for renewal in April 2007.
[src:netherlands/eu] The EURid registry software is based on the DNS.be software and domains are physically renewed at the end of the month of their anniversary of registration.
[src:netherlands/eu] This process differs from more sophisticated registries like that of .com TLD and other ccTLDs that operate on a daily basis.
[src:netherlands/eu] As with any post-landrush phase, an extension shrinks as the *Junk Dump* takes effect.
[src:netherlands/eu] Over one year after the launch of .eu (5 July 2007), the number of .de domains registered was 11,079,557 according to the German .de registry's statistics page, while number of German owned .eu domains according to EURid's statistics page was 796,561.
[src:netherlands/eu] The number of .uk domains registered was 6,038,732 according to .uk registry Nominet's statistics page.
[src:netherlands/eu] The number of apparently UK owned .eu domains was 344,584.
[src:netherlands/eu] The extent of the shrinkage of .eu ccTLD is difficult to estimate because EURid does not publish detailed statistics on the number of new domains registered each day.
[src:netherlands/eu] Instead it provides only a single figure for the number of active domains.
[src:netherlands/eu] The number of new registrations are combined with numbers of domains registered.
[src:netherlands/eu] Approximately 250,000 .eu domains were either deleted or moved into quarantine by 30 April 2007.
[src:netherlands/eu] In the intervening years the renewal rate has stabilised to approximately 80%, which is above the industry average.
[src:netherlands/eu] As of November 2019, according to the Tranco rank, the top 100 thousand most popular domains in the world included over 200 .eu domains.
[src:netherlands/eu] The commission announced on 27 April 2018 that it would like to open registration to all EU and EEA citizens, including those living outside the EU.
[src:netherlands/eu] The Parliament, the council, and the Commission reached an agreement on this in December 2018, and the corresponding regulation passed the Parliament on 31 January 2019.
[src:netherlands/eu] The 317,000 British .eu domain names were subject to Brexit negotiations because the .eu domain is reserved for European Union use.
[src:netherlands/eu] The .eu Brexit would have occurred on 30 March 2020, in case of no deal, but had since been postponed to January 2021.
[src:netherlands/eu] The UK-EU free trade deal does not cover .eu domains.
[src:netherlands/eu] The United Kingdom Government released guidance for British citizens regarding .eu domains in October 2020, and .eu holders with a British address attached have been contacted twice by the domain registry regarding their domains – once in October 2020, once in December 2020.
[src:netherlands/eu] British citizens had their .eu domains suspended on 1 January 2021 for six months, and then withdrawn on 1 July 2021 after a grace period to allow EU/EEA citizens to update the registration information to show their non-UK address.
[src:netherlands/eu] From 1 January 2022, they were revoked and made available for registration by other entities.
[src:netherlands/eu] This is the first case of its kind where an institution managing an internet top-level domain has withdrawn domains *en masse* for an entire country.
[src:netherlands/eu] The second-level domain .europa.eu has been reserved for EU institution sites, with institutions and agencies making the switch from .eu.int to .europa.eu domains on the Europe day of 9 May 2006.
[src:netherlands/eu] EURid has a rule that the second-level domain name must be in the same script as the top-level domain, so Cyrillic second-level domains must go under .ею instead of .eu, and all domain names under .ею must be spelt using Cyrillic.
[src:netherlands/eu] Older Cyrillic domains under .eu were cloned into .ею at its launch.
[src:netherlands/eu] As of March 2024, there are 1,486 registered domains under .ею.
[src:netherlands/eu] An application for a top-level domain using Greek letters, **.ευ** was submitted in 2016.
[src:netherlands/eu] The application was originally turned down because it was too visually similar to .eu.
[src:netherlands/eu] The Greek name of the EU is Ευρωπαϊκή Ένωση (ΕΕ), but .εε would be too visually similar to .ee, the top-level domain of Estonia.
[src:netherlands/eu] In 2019 steps were taken towards approving .ευ as a domain.
[src:netherlands/eu] As of March 2024, there are 2,595 registered domains under .ευ.
[src:netherlands/eu] Domain name speculation, domain name warehousing and cybersquatting are always features of the launch of any new TLD; however, this was more widespread in the case of the .eu launch.
[src:netherlands/eu] Bob Parsons, CEO and co-founder of GoDaddy, criticized the landrush process designed by EURid.
[src:netherlands/eu] Particularly, he condemned the use of shell companies by some registrars.
[src:netherlands/eu] These "phantom" registrars effectively had hundreds of opportunities of registering a domain whereas a genuine registrar effectively only had one opportunity to register the same domain.
[src:netherlands/eu] Thus some registrants were crowded out of the .eu landrush process and many generic .eu domain names are now owned by the companies using these "phantom" registrars.
[src:netherlands/eu] Patrik Lindén, spokesman for EURid at the time, denied the allegations by Parsons, stating that "[EURid] verified that each registrar was an individual legal entity.
[src:netherlands/eu] Each had to sign an agreement with us, and prepay €10,000." Parsons did not dispute that each registrar was a separate legal entity, but noted that creating such entities was trivial: "Mr.
[src:netherlands/eu] Linden seemed proud that the EURid registry verified that each applicant was a legal entity before it was accredited.
[src:netherlands/eu] Take a moment and think about what that means.
[src:netherlands/eu] You can form a "legal entity" for $50 – an LLC – and you are good to go.
[src:netherlands/eu] While speculative activity occurred with the launch of other domains, it was the scale of the activity that called into question the competence of EURid in protecting the integrity of eu ccTLD.
[src:netherlands/eu] The EURid organisation investigated some allegations of abuse, and in July 2006 announced the suspension of over 74,000 domain names and that they were suing 400 registrars for breach of contract.
[src:netherlands/eu] The status of the domains was changed from *active* to *on-hold*.
[src:netherlands/eu] This meant that the domains could not be moved or have their ownership changed.
[src:netherlands/eu] The registrars also lost their access to the EURid registration database meaning that they could no longer register .eu domain names.
[src:netherlands/eu] The legal action relates to the practice of domain name warehousing, whereby large numbers of domain names are registered, often by registrars, with the intention of subsequently selling them on to third parties.
[src:netherlands/eu] EURid rules state that applications for domains can only be made after a legitimate application has been made to a registrar.
[src:netherlands/eu] The 74,000 applications were made in the name of only three Cyprus registered companies – Ovidio Ltd., Fausto Ltd. and Gabino Ltd.
[src:netherlands/eu] The affected registrars, joined in the action by the affected registrants, obtained a provisional order from the Court of First Instance in Brussels, Belgium on 27 September 2006.
[src:netherlands/eu] The court ordered EURid to release the blocked domain names or else pay a fine of €25,000 per hour for each affected domain name.
[src:netherlands/eu] EURid complied with the court order and changed the status of the domains from *on-hold* to *active* and restored EURid registration database access to the affected registrars.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The **Netherlands**, informally **Holland**, is a country in Northwestern Europe, with overseas territories in the Caribbean.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It is the largest of the four constituent countries of the Kingdom of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands consists of twelve provinces and three overseas special municipalities.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] European Netherlands has land borders with Germany to the east and with Belgium to the south, and a coastline to the north and west.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It shares maritime borders with the United Kingdom, Germany, and Belgium in the North Sea.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The official language is Dutch, with West Frisian as a secondary official language in the province of Friesland.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Dutch, English, and Papiamento are official in the Caribbean territories.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] People from the Netherlands are referred to as Dutch.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] With a population of over 18 million people, all living within a total area of 41,850 km2 (16,160 sq mi)—of which the land area is 33,500 km2 (12,900 sq mi)—the Netherlands is the 26th most densely populated country, with a density of 541 people per square kilometre (1,400 people/sq mi).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Nevertheless, it is the world's second largest exporter of food and agricultural products by value, owing to its fertile soil, mild climate, intensive agriculture, and inventiveness.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The four largest cities in the Netherlands are Amsterdam, Rotterdam, The Hague and Utrecht.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Amsterdam is the country's most populous city and the nominal capital, though the primary national political institutions are in The Hague.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands has been a parliamentary constitutional monarchy with a unitary structure since 1848.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The country has a tradition of pillarisation (separation of citizens into groups by religion and political beliefs) and a long record of social tolerance, having legalised prostitution and euthanasia, along with maintaining a liberal drug policy.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands allowed women's suffrage in 1919 and was the first country to legalise same-sex marriage in 2001.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] A developed country, its mixed-market advanced economy is the eighteenth-largest in the world, and has the eleventh-highest per capita income globally.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Hague holds the seat of the States General, cabinet, and Supreme Court.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Port of Rotterdam is the busiest in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Schiphol is the busiest airport in the Netherlands, and the fourth busiest in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands is a founding member of the European Union, eurozone, G10, NATO, OECD, and World Trade Organization, as well as a part of the Schengen Area and the trilateral Benelux Union.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It hosts intergovernmental organisations and international courts, many of which are in The Hague.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The countries that comprise the region called the Low Countries (Netherlands, Belgium, and Luxembourg) all have comparatively the same toponymy.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Place names with *Neder*, *Nieder*, *Nedre*, *Nether*, *Lage(r)* or *Low(er)* (in Germanic languages) and *Bas* or *Inferior* (in Romance languages) are in use in low-lying places all over Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Romans made a distinction between the Roman provinces of downstream Germania Inferior (nowadays part of Belgium and the Netherlands) and upstream Germania Superior.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Thus, in the case of the Low Countries and the Netherlands, the geographical location of this *lower* region is more or less downstream and near the sea, compared to that of the upper region of Germania Superior.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The designation 'Low' returned in the 10th-century Duchy of Lower Lorraine, which covered much of the Low Countries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dukes of Burgundy used the term *les pays de par deçà* ("the lands over here") for the Low Countries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Under Habsburg rule, this became *pays d'embas* ("lands down here").
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] This was translated as *Neder-landen* in contemporary Dutch official documents.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] From a regional point of view, *Niderlant* was also the area between the Meuse and the lower Rhine in the late Middle Ages.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] From the mid-sixteenth century, the "Low Countries" and the "Netherlands" lost their original deictic meaning.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In most Romance languages, the term "Low Countries" is officially used as the name for the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The term *Holland* has frequently been used informally to refer to the whole of the modern country of the Netherlands in various languages, including Dutch and English.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In some languages, Holland is used as the formal name for the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, Holland is a region within the Netherlands that consists of the two provinces of North and South Holland.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Formerly these were a single province, and earlier the County of Holland, which also included parts of present-day Utrecht.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The emphasis on Holland during the formation of the Dutch Republic, the Eighty Years' War, and the Anglo-Dutch Wars in the 17th and 18th centuries made Holland a *pars pro toto* for the entire country.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Many Dutch people object to the country being referred to as *Holland* instead of *the Netherlands*, on much the same grounds as many Welsh or Scottish people object to the United Kingdom being referred to as England.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In particular, those from regions other than Holland find it undesirable or misrepresentative to use the term Holland for the whole country, as the Holland region only comprises two of the twelve provinces, and 38% of Dutch citizens.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The use of the term in this context by the southern Dutch is in a derogatory fashion.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the southern province of Limburg, the term is used for the Dutch from the other 11 provinces.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The oldest human (Neanderthal) traces in the Netherlands, believed to be about 250,000 years old, were found near Maastricht.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] At the end of the Ice Age, the nomadic late Upper Palaeolithic Hamburg culture (13,000–10,000 BC) hunted reindeer in the area, using spears.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The later Ahrensburg culture (11,200–9,500 BC) used bow and arrow.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] From Mesolithic Maglemosian-like tribes (c.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] 8000 BC), the world's oldest canoe was found in Drenthe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Indigenous late Mesolithic hunter-gatherers from the Swifterbant culture (c.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] 5600 BC), related to the southern Scandinavian Ertebølle culture, were strongly linked to rivers and open water.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Between 4800 and 4500 BC, the Swifterbant people started to adopt from the neighbouring Linear Pottery culture the practice of animal husbandry, and between 4300 and 4000 BC agriculture.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Funnelbeaker culture (4300–2800 BC) erected the dolmens, large stone grave monuments found in Drenthe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] There was a quick transition from the Funnelbeaker farming culture to the pan-European Corded Ware pastoralist culture (c.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the southwest, the Seine-Oise-Marne culture—related to the Vlaardingen culture (c.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] 2600 BC)—survived well into the Neolithic period, until it too was succeeded by the Corded Ware culture.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The subsequent Bell Beaker culture (2700–2100 BC) introduced metalwork in copper, gold and later bronze and opened new international trade routes, reflected in copper artefacts.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Finds of rare bronze objects suggest that Drenthe was a trading centre in the Bronze Age (2000–800 BC).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Bell Beaker culture developed locally into the Barbed-Wire Beaker culture (2100–1800 BC) and later the Elp culture (1800–800 BC), a Middle Bronze Age culture marked by earthenware pottery.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The southern region became dominated by the related Hilversum culture (1800–800 BC).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] From 800 BC onwards, the Iron Age Celtic Hallstatt culture became influential, replacing the Hilversum culture.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Iron ore brought a measure of prosperity and was available throughout the country.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Smiths travelled from settlement to settlement with bronze and iron, fabricating tools on demand.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The King's grave of Oss (700 BC) was found in a burial mound, the largest of its kind in Western Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The deteriorating climate in Scandinavia from 850 BC and 650 BC might have triggered the migration of Germanic tribes from the North.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] By the time this migration was complete, around 250 BC, a few general cultural and linguistic groups had emerged.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The North Sea Germanic Ingaevones inhabited the northern part of the Low Countries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] They would later develop into the Frisii and the early Saxons.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Weser–Rhine Germanic (or Istvaeones) extended along the middle Rhine and Weser and inhabited the Low Countries south of the great rivers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] These tribes would eventually develop into the Salian Franks.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] 450 BC to the Roman conquest) expanded over a wide range, including the southern area of the Low Countries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Some scholars have speculated that even a third ethnic identity and language, neither Germanic nor Celtic, survived in the Netherlands until the Roman period, the Nordwestblock culture.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The first author to describe the coast of Holland and Flanders was the geographer Pytheas, who noted in c.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] 325 BC that in these regions, "more people died in the struggle against water than in the struggle against men." During the Gallic Wars, the area south and west of the Rhine was conquered by Roman forces under Julius Caesar from 57 BC to 53 BC.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Caesar describes two main Celtic tribes living in what is now the southern Netherlands: the Menapii and the Eburones.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Notable towns would arise along the Limes Germanicus: Nijmegen and Voorburg.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the first part of Gallia Belgica, the area south of the Limes became part of the Roman province of Germania Inferior.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The area to the north of the Rhine, inhabited by the Frisii, remained outside Roman rule, while the Germanic border tribes of the Batavi and Cananefates served in the Roman cavalry.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Batavi rose against the Romans in the Batavian rebellion of AD 69 and were defeated.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Batavi later merged with other tribes into the confederation of the Salian Franks, whose identity emerged in the first half of the third century.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Salian Franks appear in Roman texts as both allies and enemies.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] They were forced by the confederation of the Saxons from the east to move over the Rhine into Roman territory in the fourth century.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] From their new base in West Flanders and the Southwest Netherlands, they were raiding the English Channel.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Roman forces pacified the region but did not expel the Franks, who continued to be feared at least until the time of Julian the Apostate (358) when Salian Franks were allowed to settle as *foederati* in Texandria.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] After the Roman government in the area collapsed in roughly the year 406, the Franks expanded their territories into numerous kingdoms.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] By the 490s, Clovis I had conquered and united all these territories in the southern Netherlands in one Frankish kingdom, and from there continued his conquests into Gaul.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] During this expansion, Franks migrating to the south (modern territory of France and Walloon part of Belgium) eventually adopted the Vulgar Latin of the local population.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] A widening cultural divide grew with the Franks remaining in their original homeland in the north (i.e. the southern Netherlands and Flanders), who kept on speaking Old Frankish, which by the ninth century had evolved into Old Low Franconian or Old Dutch.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] A Dutch-French language boundary hence came into existence.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] To the north of the Franks, climatic conditions improved, and during the Migration Period Saxons, the closely related Angles, Jutes, and Frisii settled the coast.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Many moved on to England and came to be known as Anglo-Saxons, but those who stayed would be referred to as Frisians and their language as Frisian.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Frisian was spoken along the entire southern North Sea coast.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] By the seventh century, a Frisian Kingdom (650–734) under King Aldegisel and King Redbad emerged with Traiectum (Utrecht) as its centre of power, while Dorestad was a flourishing trading place.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Between 600 and 719, the strategic cities and commercial hubs of the Rhine delta were fiercely contested by the Frisian Kingdom and the expanding Frankish Empire.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 734, at the Battle of the Boarn, the Frisians were defeated after a series of wars.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] With the approval of the Franks, the Anglo-Saxon missionary Willibrord converted the Frisian people to Christianity and established the Archdiocese of Utrecht.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, his successor Boniface was murdered by the Frisians in 754.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Frankish Carolingian Empire controlled much of Western Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 843, it was divided into three parts—East, Middle, and West Francia.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Most of present-day Netherlands became part of Middle Francia, which was a weak kingdom and subject to numerous partitions and annexation attempts by its stronger neighbours.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It comprised territories from Frisia in the north to the Kingdom of Italy in the south.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Around 850, Lothair I of Middle Francia acknowledged the Viking Rorik of Dorestad as ruler of most of Frisia.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] When the kingdom of Middle Francia was partitioned in 855, the lands north of the Alps passed to Lothair II and subsequently were named Lotharingia.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] After he died in 869, Lotharingia was partitioned, into Upper and Lower Lotharingia, the latter comprising the Low Countries that became part of East Francia in 870.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Around 879, another Viking expedition led by Godfrid, Duke of Frisia, raided the Frisian lands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Resistance to the Vikings, if any, came from local nobles, who gained in stature as a result, and that laid the basis for the disintegration of Lower Lotharingia into semi-independent states.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] One of these local nobles was Gerolf of Holland, who assumed lordship in Frisia, and Viking rule came to an end.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Holy Roman Empire ruled much of the Low Countries in the 10th and 11th century but was not able to maintain political unity.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Powerful local nobles turned their cities, counties and duchies into private kingdoms that felt little sense of obligation to the emperor.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Holland, Hainaut, Flanders, Gelre, Brabant, and Utrecht were in a state of almost continual war or paradoxically formed personal unions.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] As Frankish settlement progressed from Flanders and Brabant, the area quickly became Old Low Franconian (or Old Dutch).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Around 1000 AD, agrarian conditions started to improve, which led to increase in population, reclamation of wasteland by farmers, and steady growth of trade and industry.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Towns grew around monasteries and castles, and a mercantile middle class began to develop in these urban areas, especially in Flanders, and later Brabant.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Wealthy cities started to buy certain privileges for themselves from the sovereign.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Around 1100 AD, farmers from Flanders and Utrecht began draining and cultivating uninhabited swampy land in the western Netherlands, making the emergence of the County of Holland as the centre of power possible.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The title of Count of Holland was fought over in the Hook and Cod Wars between 1350 and 1490.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Cod faction consisted of the more progressive cities, while the Hook faction consisted of the conservative noblemen.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] These noblemen invited Duke Philip the Good of Burgundy to conquer Holland.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Most of the Imperial and French fiefs in what is now the Netherlands and Belgium were united in a personal union by Philip the Good in 1433.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The House of Valois-Burgundy and their Habsburg heirs would rule the Low Countries from 1384 to 1581.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The new rulers defended Dutch trading interests.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The fleets of the County of Holland defeated the fleets of the Hanseatic League several times.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Amsterdam grew and in the 15th century became the primary trading port in Europe for grain from the Baltic region.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Amsterdam distributed grain to the major cities of Belgium, Northern France and England.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] This trade was vital because Holland could no longer produce enough grain to feed itself.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Land drainage had caused the peat of the former wetlands to reduce to a level that was too low for drainage to be maintained.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Under Habsburg Charles V, all fiefs in the current Netherlands region were united into the Seventeen Provinces, which included most of present-day Belgium, Luxembourg, and parts of France and Germany.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1568, under Phillip II, the Eighty Years' War between the Provinces and their Spanish ruler began.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Duke of Alba attempted to suppress the Protestant movement in the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Netherlanders were "burned, strangled, beheaded, or buried alive" by his "Blood Council" and Spanish soldiers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Bodies were displayed along roads to terrorise the population into submission.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Alba boasted of having executed 18,600; this figure does not include those who perished by war and famine.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The first great siege was Alba's effort to capture Haarlem and thereby cut Holland in half.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It dragged on from December 1572 to the next summer, when Haarlemers finally surrendered on 13 July upon the promise that the city would be spared from being sacked.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It was a stipulation Don Fadrique was unable to honour, when his soldiers mutinied, angered over pay owed and the miserable conditions of the campaign.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] On 4 November 1576, Spanish tercios seized Antwerp and subjected it to the worst pillage in the Netherlands' history.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The citizens resisted but were overcome; seven thousand were killed and a thousand buildings were torched.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] After the sack of Antwerp, delegates from Catholic Brabant, Protestant Holland and Zeeland agreed to join Utrecht and William the Silent in driving out Spanish troops and forming a new government for the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Don Juan of Austria, the new Spanish governor, was forced to concede initially, but within months returned to active hostilities.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dutch looked for help from the Protestant Elizabeth I of England, but she initially stood by her commitments to the Spanish in the Treaty of Bristol of 1574.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] When the next large-scale battle occurred at Gembloux in 1578, the Spanish forces won easily.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In light of the defeat at Gembloux, the southern states of the Seventeen Provinces distanced themselves from the rebels in the north with the 1579 Union of Arras.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Opposing them, the northern half of the Seventeen Provinces forged the Union of Utrecht in which they committed to support each other against the Spanish.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Union of Utrecht is seen as the foundation of the modern Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Spanish troops sacked Maastricht in 1579, killing over 10,000 civilians.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1581, the northern provinces adopted the Act of Abjuration, the declaration of independence in which the provinces officially deposed Philip II.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Against the rebels Philip could draw on the resources of the Spanish Empire.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Elizabeth I sympathised with the Dutch struggle and sent an army of 7,600 soldiers to aid them.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] English forces faced the Spanish in the Netherlands under the Duke of Parma in a series of largely indecisive actions that tied down significant numbers of Spanish troops and bought time for the Dutch to reorganise their defences.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The war continued until 1648, when Spain under King Philip IV recognised the independence of the seven north-western provinces in the Peace of Münster.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Parts of the southern provinces became *de facto* colonies of the new republican-mercantile empire.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] After the declaration of independence, the provinces of Holland, Zeeland, Groningen, Friesland, Utrecht, Overijssel, and Gelderland entered into a confederation.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] All these duchies, lordships and counties enjoyed a significant degree of autonomy and were governed by their own administrative bodies known as the States-Provincial.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The confederal government, known as the States General, was headquartered in The Hague and comprised representatives from each of the seven provinces.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The sparsely populated region of Drenthe was part of the republic, albeit not considered a province in its own right.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Moreover, during the Eighty Years' War, the Republic came to occupy a number of Generality Lands in Flanders, Brabant and Limburg.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] These areas were primarily inhabited by Roman Catholics and lacked a distinct governmental structure of their own.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] They were used as a buffer zone between the Republic and the Spanish-controlled Southern Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] During the Dutch Golden Age of the 17th century, the Dutch Empire grew to become one of the major seafaring and economic powers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Dutch science, military and art (especially painting) were among the most acclaimed in the world.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] By 1650, the Dutch owned 16,000 merchant ships.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dutch East India Company and the Dutch West India Company established colonies and trading posts all over the world.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dutch settlement in North America began with the founding of New Amsterdam in 1614.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In South Africa, the Dutch settled the Cape Colony in 1652.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Dutch colonies in South America were established along the many rivers in the fertile Guyana plains, among them Colony of Surinam (now Suriname).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In Asia, the Dutch established a presence in India, the Dutch East Indies (now Indonesia), Formosa (now Taiwan), and the only western trading post in Japan, Dejima.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] During the period of Proto-industrialisation, the empire received 50% of textiles and 80% of silks import from the India's Mughal Empire.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Many economic historians regard the Netherlands as the first thoroughly capitalist country.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In early modern Europe, it had the wealthiest trading city in Amsterdam, and the first full-time stock exchange.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The inventiveness of the traders led to insurance and retirement funds as well as phenomena such as the boom-bust cycle, the world's first asset-inflation bubble, the tulip mania of 1636–1637, and the world's first bear raider, Isaac le Maire.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1672 – known in Dutch history as the Rampjaar (Disaster Year) – the Dutch Republic was attacked by France, England and two German bishoprics simultaneously, in what would become known as the Franco-Dutch War.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] At sea, it could successfully prevent the English and French navies from blockading the western shores.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] On land the Republic was almost overrun by the advancing French and German armies from the east, but the Dutch managed to turn the tide by inundating parts of Holland.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] From 1672 to 1712, the Republic, led by William III of Orange and Anthonie Heinsius would regularly clash with France in what some historians have come to call the *Forty Years' War*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the Nine Years' War and the War of the Spanish Succession, the Republic was at the centre of anti-French coalitions.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dutch ultimately successfully defended the Spanish Netherlands, established a barrier there, and their troops proved central to the alliance which halted French territorial expansion in Europe until a new cycle began in 1792 with the French Revolutionary Wars.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, the wars left them effectively bankrupt, and inflicted permanent damage on the Dutch merchant navy; while they remained the dominant economic power in the Far East, Britain took over as the pre-eminent global commercial and maritime power.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Between 1590 and 1713, the Dutch army had been one of Europe's largest and most capable armies.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, after the conclusion of the War of the Spanish Succession, other major powers, such as Prussia, Austria, Britain, and Russia, significantly expanded their military forces.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Republic struggled to match these developments, and gradually assumed the status of a mid-tier power.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, historians have sometimes overstated the extent of this decline, especially when considering the period up to the 1750s.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the 18th century, the Dutch Republic was in a state of general decline, with economic competition from England and long-standing rivalries between the two main factions in Dutch society: the republican *Staatsgezinden* and the supporters of the stadtholder, the *Prinsgezinden*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] With the armed support of revolutionary France, Dutch republicans proclaimed the Batavian Republic, modelled after the French Republic and rendering the Netherlands a unitary state on 19 January 1795.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The stadtholder William V of Orange had fled to England.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] From 1806 to 1810, the Kingdom of Holland was set up by Napoleon Bonaparte as a puppet kingdom governed by his brother Louis Bonaparte.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, King Louis Bonaparte tried to serve Dutch interests instead of his brother's, and he was forced to abdicate on 1 July 1810.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Emperor sent in an army and the Netherlands became part of the French Empire until November 1813, when Napoleon was defeated in the Battle of Leipzig.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] William Frederick, son of the last stadtholder, returned to the Netherlands in 1813 and proclaimed himself Sovereign Prince.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Two years later, the Congress of Vienna added the southern Netherlands to the north to create a strong country on the northern border of France.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] William Frederick raised this United Netherlands to the status of a kingdom and proclaimed himself as King William I in 1815.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] William became hereditary Grand Duke of Luxembourg in exchange for his German possessions.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, the Southern Netherlands had been culturally separate from the north since 1581, and rebelled.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The south gained independence in 1830 as Belgium (recognised by the Northern Netherlands in 1839 as the Kingdom of the Netherlands was created by decree), while the personal union between Luxembourg and the Netherlands was severed in 1890, when William III died without a surviving male heir.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Salic Law prevented his daughter Queen Wilhelmina from becoming the next Grand Duchess.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Belgian Revolution and the Java War in the Dutch East Indies brought the Netherlands to the brink of bankruptcy.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] However, the Cultivation System was introduced in 1830; in the Dutch East Indies, 20% of village land had to be devoted to government crops for export.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The policy brought the Dutch enormous wealth and made the colony self-sufficient.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands abolished slavery in its colonies in 1863.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Enslaved people in Suriname would be fully free only in 1873.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands remained neutral during World War I, in part because the import of goods through the Netherlands proved essential to German survival until the blockade by the British Royal Navy in 1916.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] That changed in World War II, when Germany invaded the Netherlands on 10 May 1940.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Rotterdam Blitz forced most of the Dutch army to surrender.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] During the occupation, over 100,000 Dutch Jews were transported to Nazi extermination camps; only a few survived.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Dutch workers were conscripted for forced labour in Germany, civilians who resisted were killed in reprisal for attacks on German soldiers, and the countryside was plundered for food.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Although there were thousands of Dutch who risked their lives by hiding Jews from the Germans, over 20,000 Dutch fascists joined the Waffen SS.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Political collaborators were members of the fascist NSB, the only legal political party in the occupied Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] On 8 December 1941, the Dutch government-in-exile in London declared war on Japan, but could not prevent the Japanese occupation of the Dutch East Indies.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] More than 20,000 people died from starvation during the Dutch famine of 1944–1945.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1944–45, the First Canadian Army liberated much of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Soon after VE Day, the Dutch fought a colonial war against the new Republic of Indonesia.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1954, the Charter for the Kingdom of the Netherlands reformed the political structure as a result of international pressure to carry out decolonisation.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dutch colonies of Surinam and Curaçao and Dependencies became constituent countries within the Kingdom.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Indonesia had declared its independence in August 1945.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands was one of the founding members of Benelux and NATO.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the 1950s, the Netherlands became one of the six founding countries of the European Communities, after the 1952 establishment of the European Coal and Steel Community, and subsequent 1958 creations of the European Economic Community and European Atomic Energy Community.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1993, the former two were incorporated into the European Union.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Government-encouraged emigration efforts to reduce population density prompted some 500,000 Dutch to leave the country after the war.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The 1960s and 1970s were a time of great social and cultural change, such as rapid de-pillarisation.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Students and other youth rejected traditional mores and pushed for change in matters such as women's rights, sexuality, disarmament and environmental issues.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 2002, the euro was introduced as fiat money.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 2010, the Netherlands Antilles was dissolved after referendums on each island.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Subsequently, Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba (the BES islands) were incorporated as special municipalities.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The special municipalities are collectively known as the Caribbean Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The European Netherlands has a total area of 41,543 km2 (16,040 sq mi), including water bodies, and a land area of 33,481 km2 (12,927 sq mi).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Caribbean Netherlands has a total area of 328 km2 (127 sq mi) It lies between latitudes 50° and 54° N, and longitudes 3° and 8° E.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands is geographically very low relative to sea level and is considered a flat country, with about 26% of its area and 21% of its population below sea level.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The European part of the country is for the most part flat, with the exception of foothills in the far southeast, up to a height of no more than 322 m (1,056 ft) at the Vaalserberg, and some low hill ranges in the central parts.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Most of the areas below sea level are caused by peat extraction or achieved through land reclamation.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Since the late 16th century, large polder areas are preserved through elaborate drainage systems that include dikes, canals and pumping stations.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Much of the country was originally formed by the estuaries of three large European rivers: the Rhine (*Rijn*), the Meuse (*Maas*) and the Scheldt (*Schelde*), as well as their tributaries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The south-western part of the Netherlands is a river delta of these rivers, the Rhine–Meuse–Scheldt delta.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The European Netherlands is divided into north and south parts by the Rhine, the Waal, its main tributary branch, and the Meuse.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] These rivers functioned as a natural barrier between fiefdoms and hence historically created a cultural divide, as is evident in some phonetic traits that are recognisable on either side of what the Dutch call their "Great Rivers" (*de Grote Rivieren*).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Another significant branch of the Rhine, the IJssel river, discharges into Lake IJssel, the former Zuiderzee ('southern sea').
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Just like the previous, this river forms a linguistic divide: people to the northeast of this river speak Dutch Low Saxon dialects (except for the province of Friesland, which has its own language).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands is mostly composed of deltaic, coastal and aeolian derived sediments during the Pleistocene glacial and interglacial periods.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Nearly the entire west Netherlands is composed of the Rhine-Meuse river estuary.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the east of the Netherlands, remains are found of the last ice age, which ended approximately ten thousand years ago.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] As the continental ice sheet moved in from the north, it pushed moraine forward.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The ice sheet halted as it covered the eastern half of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] After the ice age ended, the moraine remained in the form of a long hill-line.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The cities of Arnhem and Nijmegen are built on these hills.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Over the centuries, the Dutch coastline has changed considerably as a result of natural disasters and human intervention.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Lucia's flood affected the Netherlands and neighbouring Germany, killing more than 50,000 people in one of the most destructive floods in recorded history.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Elizabeth flood of 1421 and the mismanagement in its aftermath destroyed a newly reclaimed polder, replacing it with the 72 km2 (28 mi2) *Biesbosch* tidal floodplains.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The huge North Sea flood of February 1953 caused the collapse of several dikes in the southwest Netherlands; more than 1,800 people drowned.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dutch government subsequently instituted a large-scale programme, the "Delta Works", to protect the country against future flooding, which was completed over a period of more than 40 years.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The consequences of disasters were, to an extent, increased through human activity.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Relatively high-lying swampland was drained to be used as farmland.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The drainage caused the fertile peat to contract and ground levels to drop; groundwater levels were lowered to compensate, causing the underlying peat to contract further.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Additionally, until the 19th century, peat was mined, dried, and used for fuel, further exacerbating the problem.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Even in flooded areas, peat extraction continued through turf dredging.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] To guard against floods, a series of defences against the water were contrived.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the first millennium AD, villages and farmhouses were built on hills called *terps*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Later, these terps were connected by dikes.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the 12th century, local government agencies called *"waterschappen"* ("water boards") or *"hoogheemraadschappen"* ("high home councils") started to appear, whose job it was to maintain the water level and to protect a region from floods; these agencies continue to exist.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] As the ground level dropped, the dikes by necessity grew and merged into an integrated system.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] By the 13th century windmills had come into use to pump water.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The windmills were later used to drain lakes, creating the famous polders.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1932 the *Afsluitdijk* ("Closure Dike") was completed, blocking the former *Zuiderzee* (Southern Sea) from the North Sea and thus creating the IJsselmeer (IJssel Lake).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It became part of the larger Zuiderzee Works in which four polders totalling 2,500 square kilometres (965 mi2) were reclaimed from the sea.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands is one of the countries that may suffer most from climate change.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Not only is the rising sea a problem, but erratic weather patterns may cause the rivers to overflow.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] After the 1953 disaster, the Delta Works was constructed, which is a comprehensive set of civil works throughout the Dutch coast.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The project started in 1958 and was largely completed in 1997 with the completion of the Maeslantkering.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Since then, new projects have been periodically started to renovate and renew the Delta Works.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The main goal of the Delta project was to reduce the risk of flooding in South Holland and Zeeland.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] This was achieved by raising 3,000 km (1,900 mi) of outer sea-dikes and 10,000 km (6,200 mi) of the inner, canal, and river dikes, and by closing off the sea estuaries of Zeeland.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] New risk assessments occasionally show problems requiring additional Delta project dike reinforcements.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Delta project is considered by the American Society of Civil Engineers as one of the seven wonders of the modern world.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] It is anticipated that global warming will result in a rise in sea level.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands is actively preparing for a sea-level rise.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] A politically neutral Delta Commission has formulated an action plan to cope with a sea-level rise of 1.10 m (4 ft) and a simultaneous land height decline of 10 cm (4 in).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The plan encompasses the reinforcement of existing coastal defences like dikes and dunes with 1.30 m (4.3 ft) of additional flood protection.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Climate change will not only threaten the Netherlands from the coast, but could also alter rainfall patterns and river run-off.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] To protect the country from river flooding, another programme is already being executed.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Room for the River plan grants more flow space to rivers, protects the major populated areas and allows for periodic flooding of indefensible lands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The few residents who lived in these so-called "overflow areas" have been moved to higher ground, some of that ground having been raised above anticipated flood levels.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands is already affected by climate change.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The average temperature in the Netherlands rose by more than 2°C from 1901 to 2020.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Climate change has resulted in increased frequency of droughts and heatwaves.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Because significant portions of the Netherlands have been reclaimed from the sea or otherwise are near sea level, the Netherlands is very vulnerable to sea level rise.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands has the fourth largest greenhouse gas emissions per capita of the European Union, in part due to the large number of cows.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Dutch response to climate change is driven by a number of unique factors, including larger green recovery plans by the European Union in the face of the COVID-19 and a climate change litigation case, State of the Netherlands v.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Urgenda Foundation, which created mandatory climate change mitigation through emissions reductions 25% below 1990 levels.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 2021 CO2 emissions were down 14% compared to 1990 levels.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The goal of the Dutch government is to reduce emissions in 2030 by 49%.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands has 21 national parks and hundreds of other nature reserves.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Most of these are owned by Staatsbosbeheer, the national department for forestry and nature conservation and Natuurmonumenten, a private organisation that buys, protects and manages nature reserves.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Wadden Sea in the north, with its tidal flats and wetlands, is rich in biological diversity, and is a UNESCO World Heritage Nature Site.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Eastern Scheldt, formerly the northeast estuary of the river Scheldt was designated a national park in 2002, making it the largest national park in the Netherlands at an area of 370 km2 (140 sq mi).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Phytogeographically, the European Netherlands is shared between the Atlantic European and Central European provinces of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] According to the World Wide Fund for Nature, the European territory of the Netherlands belongs to the ecoregion of Atlantic mixed forests.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In 1871, the last old original natural woods were cut down.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] These woods were planted on anthropogenic heaths and sand-drifts (overgrazed heaths) (Veluwe).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Netherlands had a 2019 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 0.6/10, ranking it 169th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The number of flying insects in the Netherlands has dropped by 75% since the 1990s.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] In the Lesser Antilles islands of the Caribbean, the territories of Curaçao, Aruba and Sint Maarten have a constituent country status within the wider Kingdom of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] Another three territories which make up the Caribbean Netherlands are designated as special municipalities.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The Caribbean Netherlands have maritime borders with Anguilla, Curaçao, France (Saint Barthélemy), Saint Kitts and Nevis, the U.S.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p01] The islands of the Caribbean Netherlands enjoy a tropical climate with warm weather all year round.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has been a constitutional monarchy since 1815 and a parliamentary democracy since 1848.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands is described as a consociational state.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Dutch politics and governance are characterised by an effort to achieve broad consensus on important issues.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, the Netherlands performs in the high range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in political representation, including elected government and inclusive suffrage.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Furthermore, the Netherlands was ranked as the 17th best electoral democracy in the world by V-Dem Democracy indices in 2023 and 9th most democratic country in the world by the Democracy Index (The Economist) in 2022.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The monarch is the head of state, at present King Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Constitutionally, the position is equipped with limited powers due to ministerial responsibility.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The executive power is formed by the government that includes the monarch and the Council of Ministers, the deliberative organ of the Dutch cabinet.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The cabinet usually consists of 13 to 16 ministers and a varying number of state secretaries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] One to three ministers are ministers without portfolio.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The council of ministers is presided over by the Prime Minister of the Netherlands, who often is the leader of the largest party of the coalition.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Prime Minister is a *primus inter pares*, with no explicit powers beyond those of the other ministers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Rob Jetten has been the prime minister since February 2026.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The cabinet is responsible to the bicameral parliament, the States General, which also has legislative powers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The 150 members of the House of Representatives, the lower house, are elected in direct elections on the basis of party-list proportional representation.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] These are held every four years, or sooner in case the cabinet falls.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The provincial assemblies, the States Provincial, are directly elected every four years as well.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The members of the provincial assemblies elect the 75 members of the Senate, the upper house, which has the power to reject laws, but not amend them.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Both trade unions and employers organisations are consulted in policymaking in the financial, economic and social areas.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] They meet regularly with the government in the Social-Economic Council.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has a tradition of social tolerance.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In the late 19th century this Dutch tradition of religious tolerance transformed into a system of pillarisation, in which religious groups coexisted separately and only interacted at the level of government.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Protection for LGBTQ and abortion rights are enshrined within the Netherlands' foreign aid policy.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] No single party has held a majority in parliament since the 19th century, and as a result, coalition cabinets had to be formed.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Since male suffrage became universal in 1917, the Dutch political system has been dominated by three families of political parties: Christian Democrats (currently the CDA), Social Democrats (currently the PvdA), and Liberals (currently the VVD).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In November 2025, the centrist-liberal Democrats 66 of Rob Jetten was the winner of a general election, securing 26 out of 150 seats in the House of Representatives.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] A cabinet formation was ongoing as of November 2025 to form a new government.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands is divided into twelve provinces, each under a King's Commissioner.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] All provinces are divided into municipalities (*gemeenten*), of which there are 342 (2023).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The country is subdivided into 21 water districts, governed by a water board (*waterschap* or *hoogheemraadschap*), each having authority in matters concerning water management.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The creation of water boards pre-dates that of the nation itself, the first appearing in 1196.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch water boards are among the oldest democratic entities in the world still in existence.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Direct elections of the water boards take place every four years.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Within the Dutch town of Baarle-Nassau, are 22 Belgian exclaves and within those are eight Dutch enclaves.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The administrative structure on the three BES islands, collectively known as the Caribbean Netherlands, is outside the twelve provinces.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] These islands have the status of *openbare lichamen (public bodies)*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In the Netherlands these administrative units are often referred to as *special municipalities*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The history of Dutch foreign policy has been characterised by its neutrality.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Netherlands is the 18th most peaceful country in the world.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Since World War II, the Netherlands has become a member of a large number of international organisations, most prominently the UN, NATO and the EU.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The foreign policy of the Netherlands is based on four basic commitments: to Atlantic co-operation, to European integration, to international development and to international law.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] One of the more controversial international issues surrounding the Netherlands is its liberal policy towards soft drugs.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The historical ties inherited from its colonial past in Indonesia and Suriname still influence the foreign relations of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Many with heritage from these countries now live permanently in the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has one of the oldest standing armies in Europe; it was first established in the late 1500s.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] After the defeat of Napoleon, the Dutch army was transformed into a conscription army.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands abandoned its neutrality in 1948 when it signed the Treaty of Brussels, and became a founding member of NATO in 1949.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch military was therefore part of the NATO strength in Cold War Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 1983 the (ceremonial) function of commander of chief of the monarch was transferred to the government, which means the monarch (nominal head of state) has no formal military function.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 1996 conscription was suspended, and the Dutch army was once again transformed into a professional army.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Since the 1990s the Dutch army has been involved in the Bosnian War and the Kosovo War, it held a province in Iraq after the defeat of Saddam Hussein, and it was engaged in Afghanistan.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has ratified many international conventions concerning war law.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands decided not to sign the UN treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The submarine service opened to women on 1 January 2017.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Korps Commandotroepen, the Special Operations Force of the Netherlands Army, is open to women, but because of the extremely high physical demands for initial training, it is almost impossible for a woman to become a commando.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch Ministry of Defence employs more than 70,000 personnel, including over 20,000 civilians and over 50,000 military personnel.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Since the 16th century, shipping, fishing, agriculture, trade, and banking have been leading sectors of the Dutch economy.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has a high level of economic freedom.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands is one of the top countries in the Global Enabling Trade Report (2nd in 2016), and was ranked the fifth most competitive economy in the world by the Swiss International Institute for Management Development in 2017.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The country was ranked the 8th most innovative nation in the world in the 2025 Global Innovation Index down from 2nd in 2018.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] As of 2020, the key trading partners of the Netherlands were Germany, Belgium, the United Kingdom, the United States, France, Italy, China and Russia.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands is one of the world's 10 leading exporting countries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Foodstuffs form the largest industrial sector.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Other major industries include chemicals, metallurgy, machinery, electrical goods, trade, services and tourism.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Examples of international Dutch companies operating in the Netherlands include Randstad NV, Heineken, KLM, financial services (ING, ABN AMRO, Rabobank), chemicals (DSM, AKZO), petroleum refining (Shell plc), electronic machinery (Philips, ASML), and satellite navigation (TomTom).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has the 17th-largest economy in the world, and ranks 11th in GDP (nominal) per capita.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has low income inequality, but wealth inequality is relatively high.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Despite ranking 11th in GDP per capita, UNICEF ranked the Netherlands 1st in child well-being in rich countries, both in 2007 and in 2013.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Amsterdam is the financial and business capital of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Amsterdam Stock Exchange (AEX), part of Euronext, is the world's oldest stock exchange and is one of Europe's largest bourses.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] As a founding member of the euro, the Netherlands replaced (for accounting purposes) its former currency, the "gulden" (guilder), on 1 January 1999.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Actual euro coins and banknotes followed on 1 January 2002.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] One euro was equivalent to 2.20371 Dutch guilders.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In the Caribbean Netherlands, the United States dollar is used instead.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands is a "conduit country" that helps to funnel profits from high-tax countries to tax havens.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] It has been ranked as the 4th largest tax haven in the world.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch location gives it prime access to markets in the United Kingdom and Germany, the Port of Rotterdam being the largest port in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Other important parts of the economy are international trade, banking and transport.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands successfully addressed the issue of public finances and stagnating job growth long before its European partners.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Amsterdam is the 5th-busiest tourist destination in Europe, with more than 4.2 million international visitors.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Since the enlargement of the EU, large numbers of migrant workers have arrived in the Netherlands from Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands continues to be one of the leading European nations for attracting foreign direct investment and is one of the five largest investors in the United States.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The economy experienced a slowdown in 2005, but in 2006 recovered to the fastest pace in six years on the back of increased exports and strong investment.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The pace of job growth reached 10-year highs in 2007.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands is the fourth-most competitive economy in the world, according to the World Economic Forum's Global Competitiveness Report.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Beginning in the 1950s, the Netherlands discovered huge natural gas resources.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The sale of natural gas generated enormous revenues for the Netherlands for decades, adding, over sixty years, hundreds of billions of euros to the government's budget, about 1.5% of GNP.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] However, the unforeseen consequences of the country's huge energy wealth affected the competitiveness of other sectors of the economy, leading to the theory of Dutch disease.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The field is operated by government-owned Gasunie and output is jointly exploited by the government, Royal Dutch Shell, and ExxonMobil.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Gas production caused earthquakes which damaged housing.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] After a large public backlash, the government decided to phase out gas production from the field.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has made notable progress in its transition to a carbon-neutral economy.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Thanks to increasing energy efficiency, energy demand shows signs of decoupling from economic growth.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The share of energy from renewable sources doubled from 2008 to 2019, with especially strong growth in offshore wind and rooftop solar.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] However, the Netherlands remains heavily reliant on fossil fuels and has a concentration of energy- and emission-intensive industries that will not be easy to decarbonise.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Its 2019 Climate Agreement defines policies and measures to support the achievement of Dutch climate targets and was developed through a collaborative process involving parties from across Dutch society.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] As of 2018, the Netherlands had one of the highest rates of carbon dioxide emissions per person in the European Union.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands' biocapacity totals only 0.8 global hectares per person in 2016, 0.2 of which are dedicated to agriculture.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch biocapacity per person is just about half of the 1.6 global hectares of biocapacity per person available worldwide.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In contrast, in 2016, the Dutch used on average 4.8 global hectares of biocapacity – their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] As a result, the Netherlands was running a biocapacity deficit of 4.0 global hectares per person in 2016.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch agricultural sector is highly mechanised, and has a strong focus on international exports.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] It employs about 4% of the Dutch labour force but produces large surpluses in the food-processing industry and accounts for 21% of the Dutch total export value.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch rank first in the European Union and second worldwide in value of agricultural exports, behind only the United States, with agricultural exports earning €80.7 billion in 2014, up from €75.4 billion in 2012.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2019 agricultural exports were worth €94.5 billion.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In an effort to reduce agricultural pollution, the Dutch government is imposing strict limits on the productivity of the farming sector, triggering Dutch farmers' protests.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] One-third of the world's exports of chilis, tomatoes, and cucumbers go through the country.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands exports one-fifteenth of the world's apples.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] A significant portion of Dutch agricultural exports consists of fresh-cut plants, flowers, and flower bulbs, the Netherlands exporting two thirds of the world's total.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Mobility on Dutch roads has grown continuously since the 1950s and now exceeds 200 billion km travelled per year, three quarters of which are done by car.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Around half of all trips in the Netherlands are made by car, 25% by bicycle, 20% walking, and 5% by public transport.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has one of the densest road networks in the world.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has a relatively high uptake of electric vehicles, as the government implemented ambitious policy on both charging infrastructure and tax benefits.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] As of 2019, the Netherlands hosts approximately 30% of all recharging stations in the European Union.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Moreover, newly sold cars in the Netherlands have on average the lowest CO2 emissions in the EU.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] About 13% of all distance is travelled by public transport, the majority of which is by train.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch rail network of 3,013 km (1,872 mi) route is also rather dense.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The network is mostly focused on passenger rail services and connects all major cities, with over 400 stations.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Trains are frequent, with two trains per hour on lesser lines, two to four trains per hour on average, and up to eight trains an hour on the busiest lines.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch national train network includes the HSL-Zuid, a high-speed line between the Amsterdam metropolitan area and the Belgian border for trains running from Paris and London, to the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Cycling is a ubiquitous mode of transport.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Almost as many kilometres are covered by bicycle as by train.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch are estimated to have at least 18 million bicycles, which makes more than one per capita, and twice as many as the circa 9 million motor vehicles on the road.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2013, the European Cyclists' Federation ranked the Netherlands and Denmark as the most bike-friendly countries in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Busy roads have received some 35,000 km of dedicated cycle tracks, physically segregated from motorised traffic.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Busy junctions are often equipped with bicycle-specific traffic lights.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] There are large bicycle parking facilities, particularly in city centres and train stations.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Port of Rotterdam is the largest port in Europe and the largest port outside East Asia, the rivers Meuse and Rhine providing excellent access to the hinterland upstream.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] As of 2022, Rotterdam was the world's tenth largest container port.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The port's main activities are petrochemical industries and general cargo handling and transshipment.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The harbour functions as an important transit point for bulk materials and between the European continent and overseas.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Volkeraksluizen between Rotterdam and Antwerp are the biggest sluices for inland navigation in terms of tonnage.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2007, the Betuweroute, a new fast freight railway from Rotterdam to Germany, was completed.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The inland shipping fleet of the Netherlands is the largest in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Passenger boats in the Netherlands includes a ferry network in Amsterdam, and waterbusses and taxis in Rotterdam.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Schiphol Airport, just southwest of Amsterdam, is the main international airport in the Netherlands, and the fourth busiest airport in Europe by number of passengers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Schiphol is the main hub for KLM, the nation's flag carrier and the world's oldest airline.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2016, the Royal Schiphol Group airports handled 70 million passengers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] All air traffic is international and Schiphol Airport is connected to over 300 destinations worldwide, more than any other European airport.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The airport is a major freight hub as well, processing 1.44 million tonnes of cargo in 2020.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Smaller international airports are in or near Eindhoven, Rotterdam, Maastricht and Groningen.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Air transport is of vital significance for the Caribbean part of the Netherlands, all islands having their own airports.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] This includes the shortest runway in the world on Saba.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands had an estimated population of 18,080,943 as of June 2025.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] It is the 6th most densely populated country in Europe and the 33rd most densely populated country in the world with a density of 424 per square kilometre (1,100/sq mi).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Between 1900 and 1950, the country's population almost doubled from 5.1 to 10 million.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] From 1950 to 2000, the population further increased, to 15.9 million.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The fertility rate in the Netherlands is 1.39 children per woman (2024), which is high compared with many other European countries, but below the rate of 2.1 children per woman required for natural population replacement.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has one of the oldest populations in the world, with the average age of 42.7 years.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Life expectancy is high in the Netherlands: 84.3 years for newborn girls and 79.7 for boys (2020 estimate).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Dutch are the tallest people in the world, by nationality, with an average height of 1.81 metres (5 ft 11.3 in) for men and 1.67 metres (5 ft 5.7 in) for women in 2009.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The average height of young men in the Netherlands increased from 5 feet, 4 inches to approximately 6 feet between the 1850s until the early 2000s.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The country has a migration rate of 1.9 migrants per 1,000 inhabitants per year.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The majority of the population of the Netherlands is ethnically Dutch.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2022, the population was 74.8% ethnically Dutch, 8.3% other European, 2.4% Turkish, 2.4% Moroccan, 2.0% Indonesian, 2.0% Surinamese, and 8.1% others.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Some 150,000 to 200,000 people living in the Netherlands are expatriates, mostly concentrated in and around Amsterdam and The Hague, now constituting almost 10% of the population of these cities.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Significant minorities in the country include Frisians 700,000, Jews 41,000-45,000 and the Roma and the Sinti 40,000.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] According to Eurostat, in 2010 there were 1.8 million foreign-born residents in the Netherlands, corresponding to 11.1% of the total population.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Of these, 1.4 million (8.5%) were born outside the EU and 0.43 million (2.6%) were born in another EU Member State.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2022, there were 4.4 million residents in the Netherlands with at least one foreign-born parent.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Over half the young people in Amsterdam and Rotterdam have a non-western background, as of 2006.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Dutch people, or descendants of Dutch people, are found in migrant communities worldwide, notably in South Africa and the United States.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Randstad is the country's largest conurbation in the west of the country and contains the four largest cities: Amsterdam in the province North Holland, Rotterdam and The Hague in the province South Holland, and Utrecht in the province Utrecht.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Randstad has a population of about 8.2 million inhabitants and is the 5th largest metropolitan area in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] According to Dutch Central Statistics Bureau, in 2015, 28 per cent of the Dutch population had a spendable income above 45,000 euros (which does not include spending on health care or education).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The official language of the Netherlands is Dutch, which is spoken by the vast majority of inhabitants.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The dialects most spoken in the Netherlands are the Brabantian-Hollandic dialects.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Besides Dutch, West Frisian is recognised as a second official language in the northern province of Friesland (*Fryslân* in West Frisian).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] West Frisian has a formal status for government correspondence in that province.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Four other languages are protected under the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The first of these recognised regional languages is Low Saxon (*Nedersaksisch* in Dutch).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Low Saxon consists of several dialects of the Low German language spoken in the north and east of the Netherlands, like Tweants in the region of Twente, and Drents in the province of Drenthe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Limburgish is recognised as a regional language.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] It consists of Dutch varieties of Meuse-Rhenish and is spoken in the south-eastern province of Limburg.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Yiddish and the Romani language were recognised in 1996 as non-territorial languages.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] English has a formal status in the special municipalities of Saba and Sint Eustatius.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Papiamento has a formal status in the special municipality of Bonaire.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has a long tradition of learning foreign languages, formalised in Dutch education laws.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Some 90% of the total population are able to converse in English, 70% in German, and 29% in French.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] English is a mandatory course in all secondary schools.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In most lower level secondary school educations (vmbo), one additional modern foreign language is mandatory during the first two years.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In higher level secondary schools (havo and vwo), the acquisition of two additional modern foreign language skills is mandatory.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Besides English, the standard modern languages are French and German, although schools can replace one of these with Chinese, Spanish, Russian, Italian, Turkish or Arabic.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Additionally, schools in Friesland teach and have exams in West Frisian.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Forms of Christianity have dominated religious life in what is now the Netherlands for more than 1,200 years, and by the middle of the sixteenth century the country was strongly Protestant (Calvinist).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The population was predominantly Christian until the late 20th century.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Although significant religious diversity remains, there has been a decline of religious adherence.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2025, Statistics Netherlands found that 58% of the total population declared itself non-religious.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Groups that represent the non-religious in the Netherlands include Humanistisch Verbond.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Catholics comprised 16% of the total population, Protestants 12%.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Muslims comprised 6% of the total population and followers of other Christian denominations and other religions (like Judaism, Buddhism and Hinduism) comprised the remaining 7%.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] A 2015 survey from another source found that Protestants outnumbered Catholics.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The southern provinces of North Brabant and Limburg have historically been strongly Catholic, and some residents consider the Catholic Church as a base for their cultural identity.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] This can be seen in for example the regional celebration of Carnival.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Protestantism in the Netherlands consists of a number of churches within various traditions.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The largest of these is the Protestant Church in the Netherlands (PKN), a united church which is Calvinist and Lutheran in orientation.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] It was formed in 2004 as a merger of the Dutch Reformed Church, the Reformed Churches in the Netherlands and a smaller Lutheran Church.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Several orthodox Calvinist and liberal churches did not merge into the PKN.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Although Christianity has become a minority in the Netherlands, there is a Bible Belt from Zeeland to the northern parts of the province Overijssel, in which orthodox Protestant beliefs remain strong.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Statistically, areas of the Bible Belt also have the highest fertility rates and the youngest populations in the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Several Christian religious holidays are national holidays (Christmas, Easter, Pentecost, and the Ascension of Jesus).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Islam is the second largest religion in the state.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Muslim population increased from the 1960 as a result of large numbers of migrant workers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] This included migrant workers from Turkey and Morocco, as well as migrants from former Dutch colonies, such as Suriname and Indonesia.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] During the 1990s, Muslim refugees arrived from countries like Bosnia and Herzegovina, Iran, Iraq, Somalia, and Afghanistan.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Since 2000 there has been raised awareness of religion, mainly due to Islamic extremism.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Another religion practised is Hinduism, with about 215,000 adherents (slightly over 1% of the population).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] There are sizeable populations of Hindu immigrants from India and Sri Lanka, and Western adherents of Hinduism-orientated new religious movements such as Hare Krishnas.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has an estimated 250,000 Buddhists or people strongly attracted to this religion, mainly ethnic Dutch people.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] There are about 30,000 Jews in the Netherlands, though the Institute for Jewish Policy Research estimates range from 30,000 to 63,000, depending on how the number is calculated.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Constitution of the Netherlands guarantees freedom of education, which means that all schools that adhere to general quality criteria receive the same government funding.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] This includes schools based on religious principles by religious groups (especially Catholic and Protestant).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Three political parties in the Dutch parliament, (CDA, and two small parties, ChristianUnion and SGP) are based upon the Christian belief.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Several Christian religious holidays are national holidays (Christmas, Easter, Pentecost and the Ascension of Jesus).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] A survey in December 2014 concluded that for the first time there were more atheists (25%) than theists (17%) in the Netherlands, while the remainder of the population was agnostic (31%) or ietsistic (27%).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2015, a vast majority of the inhabitants of the Netherlands (82%) said they had never or almost never visited a church, and 59% stated that they had never been to a church.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Of all the people questioned, 24% saw themselves as atheist, an increase of 11% compared to the previous study done in 2006.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The expected rise of spirituality has come to a halt according to research in 2015.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2006, 40% of respondents considered themselves spiritual; in 2015 this has dropped to 31%.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The number who believed in the existence of a higher power fell from 36% to 28% over the same period.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Education in the Netherlands is compulsory between the ages of 5 and 16.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] If a child does not have a "starting qualification" (HAVO, VWO or MBO 2+ degree) they are still forced to attend classes until they achieve such a qualification or reach the age of 18.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Children in the Netherlands attend elementary school from (on average) ages 4 to 12.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] It has eight grades and the first is facultative.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Based on an aptitude test, the eighth grade teacher's recommendation and the opinion of the pupil's parents or caretakers, a choice is made for one of the three main streams of secondary education.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The VMBO has four grades and is subdivided over several levels.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Successfully completing the VMBO results in a low-level vocational degree that grants access to the MBO.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The MBO (middle-level applied education) is a form of education that primarily focuses on teaching a practical trade or a vocational degree.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] With the MBO certification, a student can apply for the HBO.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The HAVO has 5 grades and allows for admission to the HBO.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The HBO (higher professional education) are universities of professional education (applied sciences) that award professional bachelor's degrees; similar to polytechnic degrees.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] An HBO degree gives access to the university system.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The VWO (comprising atheneum and gymnasium) has 6 grades and prepares for studying at a research university.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Universities offer a three-year bachelor's degree, followed by a one or two-year master's degree, which in turn can be followed by a doctoral degree programme.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Doctoral candidates in the Netherlands are generally non-tenured employees of a university.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] All Dutch schools and universities are publicly funded and managed with the exception of religious schools.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Dutch universities have a tuition fee of about 2,000 euros a year for students from the Netherlands and the EU, and 15,000 euros for non-EU students.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2016, the Netherlands maintained its position at the top of the annual Euro Health Consumer Index (EHCI), which compares healthcare systems in Europe, scoring 916 of a maximum 1,000 points.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands has been among the top three countries in each report published since 2005.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] On 48 indicators such as patient rights and information, accessibility, prevention and outcomes, the Netherlands secured its top position among 37 European countries for six years in a row.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The Netherlands was ranked first in a study in 2009 comparing the health care systems of the United States, Australia, Canada, Germany and New Zealand.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] According to the Health Consumer Powerhouse (HCP), patients have a great degree of freedom from where to buy their health insurance, to where they get their healthcare.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Healthcare decisions are made in dialogue between patients and healthcare professionals.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Healthcare in the Netherlands is split 3 ways: in somatic and mental health care and in 'cure' (short term) and 'care' (long term).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Home doctors (*huisartsen*, comparable to general practitioners) form the largest part of the first level.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Being referred by a member of the first level is mandatory for access to the second and third level.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The health care system is, in comparison to other Western countries, effective but not the most cost-effective.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Healthcare is financed by a dual system that came into effect in January 2006.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Long-term treatments, especially those that involve semi-permanent hospitalisation, and disability costs such as wheelchairs, are covered by a state-controlled mandatory insurance.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] In 2009 this insurance covered 27% of all health care expenses.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Other sources of health care payment are taxes (14%), out of pocket payments (9%), additional optional health insurance packages (4%) and a range of other sources (4%).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Health insurance in the Netherlands is mandatory.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] While Dutch residents are automatically insured by the government for AWBZ, everyone has to buy their own basic healthcare insurance, except those under 18 who are automatically covered under their parents.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Insurance companies are obliged to provide a package with a defined set of insured treatments.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] This insurance covers 41% of all health care expenses.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Insurers have to offer a universal package for everyone over 18, regardless of age or state of health – it is illegal to refuse an application or impose special conditions.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] The funding burden for all short-term health care coverage is carried 50% by employers, 45% by the insured person and 5% by the government.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Those on low incomes receive compensation to help them pay their insurance.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p02] Premiums paid by the insured are about €135 per month.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Dutch are proud of their cultural heritage, rich history in art, and involvement in international affairs.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Dutch manners are open and direct with a no-nonsense attitude—informality combined with adherence to basic behaviour.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands is one of the most secular countries in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Religion in the Netherlands is generally considered a personal matter which is not supposed to be propagated in public, although it often remains a discussion subject.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands has had many well-known painters.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] In the Middle Ages Hieronymus Bosch and Pieter Bruegel the Elder were leading Dutch pioneers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] During the Dutch Golden Age, the Dutch Republic was prosperous and witnessed a flourishing artistic movement.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The "Dutch Masters", spanning this 17th century era, included Rembrandt, Johannes Vermeer, Jan Steen, and Jacob van Ruisdael.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Famous Dutch painters of the 19th and 20th century included Vincent van Gogh and Piet Mondrian.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Literature flourished during the Dutch Golden Age, Joost van den Vondel and P.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] In the 19th century, Multatuli wrote Max Havelaar, a book about the poor treatment of the natives in the Dutch East Indies.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] *Diary of a Young Girl* by Anne Frank is the most translated book from Dutch.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Other important 20th century authors include Harry Mulisch, Jan Wolkers, Hella Haasse, Willem Frederik Hermans, Cees Nooteboom and Gerard Reve.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Various architectural styles can be distinguished in the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Romanesque architecture was built between 950 and 1250.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Gothic architecture was used from about 1230.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Gothic buildings had large windows, pointed arches and were richly decorated.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Brabantine Gothic originated with the rise of the Duchy of Brabant and spread throughout the Burgundian provinces.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Dutch Baroque architecture (1525–1630) and classicism (1630–1700) is especially evident in the west.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Other architectural styles are Art Nouveau, Expressionism, De Stijl, Traditionalism and Brutalism.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Erasmus and Spinoza were famous Dutch philosophers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens (1629–95) discovered Saturn's moon Titan, argued that light travelled as waves, invented the pendulum clock, and was the first physicist to use mathematical formulae.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Antonie van Leeuwenhoek was the first to observe and describe single-celled organisms with a microscope.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Windmills, tulips, clogs, cheese, and cannabis have grown to symbolise the Netherlands, especially among tourists.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands has multiple music traditions.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Traditional Dutch music is a genre known as "Levenslied", meaning *Song of life*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] These songs typically have a simple melody and rhythm, and a straightforward structure of verses and choruses.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Themes can be light, but are often sentimental and include love, death and loneliness.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Traditional musical instruments such as the accordion and the barrel organ are a staple of levenslied music, though in recent years many artists use synthesisers and guitars.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Contemporary Dutch rock and pop music (Nederpop) originated in the 1960s, heavily influenced by popular music from the United States and Britain.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Bands such as Shocking Blue, Golden Earring, Tee Set, Pussycat (band), George Baker Selection and Focus enjoyed international success.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] From the 1980s, more and more pop musicians started working in the Dutch language, partly inspired by the huge success of the band Doe Maar.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Current symphonic metal bands Epica, Delain, ReVamp, The Gathering, Asrai, Autumn, Ayreon and Within Temptation as well as jazz and pop singer Caro Emerald are having international success.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Metal bands like Hail of Bullets, God Dethroned, Izegrim, Asphyx, Textures, Heidevolk, and Slechtvalk are popular guests at the biggest metal festivals in Europe.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Contemporary local stars include pop singer Anouk, country pop singer Ilse DeLange, Limburgish dialect singing folk band Rowwen Hèze, rock band BLØF and duo Nick & Simon.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Early 1990s Dutch and Belgian house music came together in Eurodance project 2 Unlimited.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Selling 18 million records, the two singers in the band are the most successful Dutch music artists to this day.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Tracks like "Get Ready for This" are still popular themes of U.S. sports events.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] In the mid-1990s Dutch language rap and hip hop (*Nederhop*) came to fruition and has become popular in the Netherlands and Belgium.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Since the 1990s, Dutch electronic dance music (EDM) gained widespread popularity in the world in many forms.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Amsterdam Dance Event (ADE) is the world's leading electronic music conference and the biggest club festival for the many electronic subgenres on the planet.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands has participated in the Eurovision Song Contest since its first edition in 1956, and has won five times.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] In classical music, Jan Sweelinck is a famous Dutch 16th to 17th-century composer; Louis Andriessen is among the best-known contemporary Dutch classical composers.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Ton Koopman and Gustav Leonhardt are internationally recognised Dutch conductors, organists, and harpsichordists.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Some Dutch films – mainly by director Paul Verhoeven – have received international distribution and recognition, such as *Turkish Delight* ("*Turks Fruit*", 1973), *Soldier of Orange* ("*Soldaat van Oranje*", 1977), *Spetters* (1980), and *The Fourth Man* ("*De Vierde Man*", 1983).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Verhoeven then went on to direct big Hollywood movies like *RoboCop* (1987), *Total Recall* (1990), and *Basic Instinct* (1992), and returned with Dutch film *Black Book* ("*Zwartboek*", 2006).
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Other well-known Dutch film directors are Jan de Bont, Anton Corbijn, Dick Maas, Fons Rademakers, Alex van Warmerdam and documentary makers Bert Haanstra and Joris Ivens.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Film director Theo van Gogh achieved international notoriety in 2004 when he was murdered by Mohammed Bouyeri in the streets of Amsterdam after directing the short film *Submission*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Directors of photography from the Netherlands include Hoyte van Hoytema, Rogier Stoffers, Theo van de Sande and Robby Müller.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Internationally successful Dutch actors include Famke Janssen, Carice van Houten, Rutger Hauer, Jeroen Krabbé., Sylvia Kristel, Michiel Huisman, Sylvia Hoeks, Marwan Kenzari and Carel Struycken.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands has a well developed television market, with commercial and public broadcasters.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Imported TV programmes, as well as interviews with responses in a foreign language, are virtually always shown with the original sound and subtitled.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Only foreign shows for children are dubbed.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] TV exports from the Netherlands mostly take the form of specific formats and franchises, most notably was the internationally active TV production conglomerate Endemol, founded by Dutch media tycoons John de Mol and Joop van den Ende.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Endemol and its subsidiaries created and ran reality, talent, and game show franchises worldwide, including *Big Brother* and *Deal or No Deal*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Endemol merged with Shine Group in 2015, and again with Banijay in 2020.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Dutch cuisine is simple and straightforward, and contains many dairy products.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Breakfast and lunch are typically bread with toppings; cereal is an option.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Traditionally, dinner consists of potatoes, meat, and vegetables.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Dutch diet was high in carbohydrates and fat, reflecting the dietary needs of the labourers whose culture moulded the country.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] During the twentieth century, this diet changed and became more cosmopolitan, most global cuisines being represented in the major cities.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] In early 2014, Oxfam ranked the Netherlands as the country with the most nutritious, plentiful and healthy food.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The regions in the northeast are the least populated areas of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The late 18th century introduction of large scale agriculture means the cuisine is known for its meats.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The relative lack of farms allowed for an abundance of game and husbandry, though dishes near the coastal regions include a large amount of fish.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The various dried sausages, belonging to the metworst-family of Dutch sausages are found throughout this region.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Smoked sausages are common, of which (*Gelderse*) *rookworst* is the most renowned.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Larger sausages are eaten alongside *stamppot*, *hutspot,* or *zuurkool* (sauerkraut); whereas smaller ones are eaten as a street food.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The provinces are home to hard textured rye bread, pastries and cookies.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] As a coastal region, Friesland is home to low-lying grasslands, and thus has a cheese production in common with the Western cuisine.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Cookies are produced in great number and contain a lot of butter and sugar.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The traditional alcoholic beverages are beer (strong pale lager) and *Jenever*, a high proof juniper-flavoured spirit, that came to be known in England as gin.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] An exception within the traditional Dutch alcoholic landscape, *Advocaat*, a rich and creamy liqueur made from eggs, sugar and brandy, is native to this region.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] A by-product of the butter-making process, *karnemelk* (buttermilk), is considered typical for this region.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Seafood such as soused herring, mussels, eels, oysters and shrimps are widely available and typical for the region.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The southern Dutch cuisine consists of the cuisines of the Dutch provinces of North Brabant and Limburg and the Flemish Region in Belgium.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] It is renowned for its rich pastries, soups, stews and vegetable dishes.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] It is the only Dutch culinary region that developed an haute cuisine.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Pastries are abundant, often with rich fillings of cream, custard or fruits.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Cakes, such as the *Vlaai* from Limburg and the *Moorkop* and *Bossche bol* from Brabant, are typical pastries.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Savoury pastries abound, the *worstenbroodje* (a roll with a sausage of ground beef, literally translates into sausage bread) being the most popular.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The alcoholic beverage of the region is beer, there are many local brands, ranging from *Trappist* to *Kriek*.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands is well known for its cheese production, with internationally recognised varieties, such as Gouda, Edam, and Leyden.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Traditional cheese markets are still held in towns like Alkmaar, Gouda, and Edam.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Approximately 4.5 million of the 16.8 million people in the Netherlands are registered in one of the 35,000 sports clubs in the country.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] About two-thirds of the population between 15 and 75 participate in sports weekly.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Football is the most popular team sport, followed by field hockey and volleyball.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Tennis, gymnastics and golf are the three most widely engaged in individual sports.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Organisation of sports began at the end of the 19th century and beginning of the 20th century.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Federations for sports were established, rules were unified and sports clubs came into existence.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] A Dutch National Olympic Committee was established in 1912.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The national football team was runner-up in the World Cup of 1974, 1978, and 2010, and won the European Championship of 1988.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Of SI's 50 greatest footballers of all time, Johan Cruyff (#5), Marco van Basten (#19), Ruud Gullit (#25), and Johan Neeskens (#36) are Dutch.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The women's national team was runner-up in 2019 World Cup and won the European Championship of 2017.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands women's field hockey team won 9 out of 15 World Cups.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands baseball team have won the European championship 24 times out of 33 events.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The volleyball national women's team won the European Championship in 1995 and the World Grand Prix in 2007.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] The Netherlands has won 266 medals at the Summer Olympic Games and 110 at the Winter Olympic Games.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Joop Zoetemelk won the 1979 Vuelta a Espana, the 1980 Tour de France, and the 1985 UCI World Championship.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Jan Janssen won the 1968 Tour de France, Tom Dumoulin the 2017 Giro d'Italia.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Max Verstappen, the youngest Formula 1 driver to make his debut and to win a race, was the first Dutchman to win a Grand Prix and a Formula One World Drivers Championship.
[src:netherlands/netherlands-p03] Dutch K-1 kickboxers have won the K-1 World Grand Prix 15 times out of 19 tournaments.
[src:netherlands/nl] When cwi.nl was registered by Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica on 1986-05-01, .nl became the first active ccTLD outside the United States.
[src:netherlands/nl] Since 31 January 1996, .nl domains are registered by the Stichting Internet Domeinregistratie Nederland (SIDN, in English: Foundation for Internet Domain Registration Netherlands), based in Arnhem.
[src:netherlands/nl] Most registrars are Internet service providers, IT service bureaus and media service bureaus, but several large enterprises with many brand names have also become a registrar, or participant as SIDN calls them, which is a quite uncommon phenomenon in the domain name industry.
[src:netherlands/nl] Registrars have to pay SIDN a fee for each domain since 1 April 1996, until then registration was free.
[src:netherlands/nl] SIDN does not deal directly with registrants.
[src:netherlands/nl] In the early days, most of the registrants were universities and research departments of large companies, such as Philips Natuurkundig Laboratorium.
[src:netherlands/nl] Besides .nl, SIDN also operates .politie in a partnership with the Dutch police and .amsterdam in cooperation with the municipality of Amsterdam and Dotlocal.
[src:netherlands/nl] Official second-level domains do not exist.
[src:netherlands/nl] A number of companies have taken the opportunity to register domains like co.nl and com.nl, using them to sell third-level domains.
[src:netherlands/nl] Individuals were allowed to register a second-level .nl domain since 2003.
[src:netherlands/nl] As a forerunner, individuals were allowed to register a third-level domain since 2000.
[src:netherlands/nl] Such 'personal domains' had the form of janjansen.123.nl.
[src:netherlands/nl] They never became popular, and registration has been suspended since 2006.
[src:netherlands/nl] Because there were only around 500 of such domains registered, in contrast to about 5 million second-level domains, SIDN announced the discontinuance of personal domains as of 2008 on 4 July 2007.
[src:netherlands/nl] Unlike the majority of top level domains, .nl requires each nameserver to use a unique IP address.
[src:netherlands/nl] There must be at least two nameservers set, meaning at least two different IP addresses must be used.
[src:netherlands/nl] Other TLDs with this requirement are .ca and .cn.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city's official name is a contraction of the (archaic) Dutch *des Hertogen bosch* ('the forest of the duke').
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The duke in question was Henry I, Duke of Brabant, whose family had owned a large estate at nearby Orthen for at least four centuries.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] He founded a new town located on some forested dunes in the middle of a marsh.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] At age 26, he granted 's-Hertogenbosch city rights and the corresponding trade privileges in 1185.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This is the traditional date given by later chroniclers; the first mention in contemporaneous sources is 1196.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] His reason for founding the city was to protect his own interests against encroachment from Gelre and Holland; from its first days, he conceived of the city as a fortress.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It was destroyed in 1203 in a joint expedition of Gelre and Holland, but was soon rebuilt.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Some remnants of the original city walls remain.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In the late 14th century, a much larger wall was erected to protect the greatly expanded settled area.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Artificial waterways were dug to serve as a city moat, through which the rivers Dommel and Aa were diverted.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch became the birthplace and home of northern Renaissance painter Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1520, the city flourished, becoming the second largest population centre in the territory of the present Netherlands, after Utrecht.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city was also a center of music, and composers, such as Jheronimus Clibano, received their training at its churches.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Others held positions there: Matthaeus Pipelare was musical director at the Confraternity of Our Lady; and renowned Habsburg copyist and composer Pierre Alamire did much of his work at 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The wars of the Reformation changed the course of the city's history.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] During the Eighty Years' War, the city took the side of the Habsburg (Catholic) authorities and thwarted a Calvinist coup.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It was besieged several times by Prince Maurice of Orange, stadtholder of most of the Dutch Republic, who wanted to bring 's-Hertogenbosch under the rule of the rebel United Provinces.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city was successfully defended against Prince Maurice in 1601 and again in 1603, but it eventually fell in the 1629 siege led by his brother Frederick Henry.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In the years of Truce, before the renewed fighting after 1618, the fortifications were greatly expanded.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The surrounding marshes made a siege of the conventional type impossible, and the fortress, deemed impregnable, was nicknamed *moerasdraak*, or the Swamp Dragon.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The town was nevertheless finally conquered by Frederik Hendrik of Orange in 1629 in a typically Dutch stratagem: he diverted the rivers Dommel and Aa, created a polder by constructing a forty-kilometre (25 mile) dyke and then pumped out the water by mills.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] After a siege of three months, the city had to surrender—an enormous blow to Habsburg geo-political strategy during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This surrender cut the town off from the rest of the duchy and the area was treated by the Republic as an occupation zone without political liberties (see also Generality Lands).
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] After the Peace of Westphalia, the fortifications were again expanded.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 1672, the Dutch *rampjaar*, the city held against the army of Louis XIV of France.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 1794 French revolutionary troops under the command of Charles Pichegru attacked the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It was only weakly defended, and fell after a short siege.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Pichegru then crossed the rivers and put an end to the Dutch Republic.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Under the new Batavian Republic, established in 1795, both Catholics and *Brabanders* at last gained equal rights.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] From 1806, the city became part of the Kingdom of Holland and from 1810, it was incorporated into the First French Empire.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It was captured by the Prussians in 1814.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The next year, 1815, when the United Kingdom of the Netherlands was established, it became the capital of North Brabant.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Many newer and more modern fortresses were created in the vicinity of the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] A new canal was built, the 'Zuid-Willemsvaart', which gave the city an economic impulse.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1878, it was forbidden to build outside the ramparts.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] That led to overcrowding and the highest infant mortality in the kingdom.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] At the end of the 19th century, the very conservative city government prevented industrial investment to avoid an increase in the number of workers and the establishment of educational institutions: students were regarded as disorderly.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] As a result, the relative importance of the city diminished.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] One of the few official Nazi concentration camp complexes in Western Europe outside Germany and Austria was named after 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It operated from January 1943, to September 1944 and was known to the Germans as Herzogenbusch (see List of subcamps of Herzogenbusch).
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] About 30,000 inmates were interned in the complex during this time, of whom about 12,000 were Jews.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In the Netherlands, this camp is known as 'Kamp Vught', because the concentration camp was actually located at a heath near Vught, a village a few kilometres south of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city was occupied by German forces during World War II from 1940 to 1944.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The railway station was bombed by planes of the Royal Air Force on 16 September 1944.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city was liberated between 24 and 27 October 1944 during Operation Pheasant by British soldiers of Major-General Robert Knox Ross's 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division following the victory of the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment, of 158th Infantry Brigade over the enemy on 23–24 October.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] After the war, 's-Hertogenbosch was modernized, like many other cities in the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It was possible that it was only the geography that shielded the old town from rigorous reconstruction in those early years.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Just in time, the pendulum swung back to protecting the history of the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 1956, the council wanted to demolish the Moriaan, the oldest brick building in the Netherlands, to give traffic better access to the market square.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The permit was refused by the government and instead the building was restored, starting in 1963.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Later, city councils became much more aware of the value of historic buildings and from about the turn of the millennium, the historic fortifications are also given much attention by the authorities.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The population centres in the municipality are: Bokhoven, Crevecoeur, Deuteren (former village), Dieskant, Empel, Engelen, Gewande, 's-Hertogenbosch, Hintham, Kruisstraat, Maliskamp, Meerwijk, Orthen (former village), Oud-Empel, and Rosmalen.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Climate in this area has mild differences between highs and lows, and there is adequate rainfall year-round.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Köppen Climate Classification subtype for this climate is "Cfb" (Marine West Coast Climate/Oceanic climate).
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city of 's-Hertogenbosch has become a center of industry, education, administration and culture.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is currently the fourth city of North Brabant.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is home to many national and international businesses such as Heineken, Epic, Tyco International, SAP and many others.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Jeroen Bosch Hospital is the biggest employer in the area, with over 4,000 employees.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] There are also over 350 restaurants, pubs and cafés to be found in the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is also home to the European Ceramic Work Centre.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This is a juried international ceramic residency where they invite artists, designers and architects from around to the world to explore the medium of Ceramics.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This program was initially started in 1991 and continues to this day.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city has its own food speciality, the Bossche Bol—effectively a giant profiterole, somewhat larger than a tennis ball, which is filled with whipped cream and coated with chocolate.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The spoken language is Maaslands (the variant spoken in 's-Hertogenbosch is called *Bosch* which is placed among the Central North Brabantian dialects, although other classification systems also describe it as East Brabantian), which is very similar to colloquial Dutch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] De Toonzaal is a music venue for chamber music, improvised music, and experimental music.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] For popular music there is the venue W2 (or Willem II).
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Noordbrabants Museum is a provincial museum with an overview of works that Vincent van Gogh made in Brabant.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Design Museum Den Bosch is a modern art museum.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Bosch Art Center, is dedicated to the work of Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Other museums include the Swan Brothers' House and Museum Slager.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Also the National (Dutch) Carnavalsmuseum Oeteldonks gemintemuzejum is located in the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In the near future a new museum will be opened about the fortresses of the town and in general in Europe.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The house where the famous painter Hieronymus produced his paintings can be visited on the market square.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has a strong carnival tradition.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In its current form the story and symbolism dates from 1881 to 1883.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In these years some citizens created the legend of "Oeteldonk", whereby the city was renamed to Oeteldonk for the three day carnival.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] "Donk" is a reference to a dry place in the marsh.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The frog is widely used as a symbol during the 's-Hertogenbosch Carnival.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is also a symbol of the Oeteldonk marsh.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It was also a remark aimed at Bishop Godschalk from Den Dungen, where 'Van den Oetelaar' was a common family name.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] He had wanted to forbid the traditional festivities of Shrove Tuesday that often led to excesses.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Oeteldonk is a village and therefore every inhabitant is a farmer or a '*durske*' (a girl or young woman), eliminating class differences.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The village is headed by the Mayor "Peer vaan den Muggenheuvel tot den Bobberd".
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Each year the mayor of 's-Hertogenbosch hands over his authority to the Mayor of Oeteldonk.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] On Sunday at 11:11 AM the Mayor of Oeteldonk then receives Prince Carnaval "Prince Amadeiro XXVI" at Oeteldonk central station.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] From there a parade of all carnival clubs escorts the company to the town hall.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The citizens of 's-Hertogenbosch wear traditional outfits throughout these days.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] A so-called *boerenkiel* is worn and every year patches are designed according to that years theme which can then be stitched onto the outfit.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The *boerenkiel* is often combined with a traditional farmers bandana and a long scarf in the colors of Oeteldonk.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The tradition of the Boerenkiel and / or Bandana is very different from the carnival traditions in the rest of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Other aspects like the parade, the temporary name and the temporary flag (for Oeteldonk red, white and yellow) are very similar.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch was founded as a fortified city and that heritage can still be seen today.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] After World War II, plans were made to modernise the old city, by filling in the canals, removing or modifying some ramparts and redeveloping historic neighbourhoods.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Before these plans could come to effect, the central government declared the city a protected townscape.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Most historic elements have been preserved.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In contrast to cities like Rotterdam, 's-Hertogenbosch also survived the Second World War relatively unscathed.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Much of its historic heritage remains intact, and today there are always renovations going on in the city to preserve the many old buildings, fortifications, churches and statues for later generations.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city center has a cosy atmosphere because of the almost continuous ramparts that still surround it.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It has been molded by the multiple rivers that convene on 's-Hertogenbosch, giving the center its strange street plan so different from the usual grid plan where streets meet at right angles.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The center is dominated by Saint John's Cathedral (*Sint-Janskathedraal* in Dutch), which dates from c.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 1220 and is best known for its Brabantine Gothic design and the many sculptures of craftsmen that are sitting on almost every arc and rim along the outside of the cathedral.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 2010 an extensive restoration was completed, undoing the damage of many years of wear-and-tear and acid rain.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] On the central square is the oldest remaining brick house of the Netherlands, 'de Moriaan', which was built at the beginning of the 13th century.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In the 1960s, de Moriaan was renovated to its former glory based on a famous 16th-century Dutch painting called 'De Lakenmarkt van 's-Hertogenbosch' ('The fabric market of 's-Hertogenbosch').
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The town hall is an original 14th-century Gothic building.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] After the town was conquered by the Dutch Republic in 1629, it received a new facade in the style of Dutch Baroque architecture.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It showcased the authority of the new masters, just like the new town hall in Maastricht would.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Hidden below the old city is a canal network called the Binnendieze, which once spanned 22 km (14 mi).
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It started out as a regular river, the Dommel, running through the city in medieval times.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Due to a lack of space in the city, people started building their houses and roads over the river.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Later, the Binnendieze functioned as a sewer and fell into disrepair.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In recent decades, the remaining sixth part of the old waterway system has been renovated, and it is possible to take several guided subterranean boat trips through it.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has an extensive and almost complete fifteenth-to-seventeenth-century city fortification.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It was made to profit from the city's strong defensive position, lying on a sandy hill in the center of a large swamp fed by many rivers.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This also caused the main ramparts to be preserved, because they were crucial in keeping out the water.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 2004 the city was awarded the title *European Fortress City of the year*.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In the years that followed it restored many of the city defenses to much of their old glory.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Apart from small sections of medieval walls, the main structure of the fortification is a late-medieval (fifteenth-century) wall.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The upper sections were removed when cannon became more powerful, and polygonal bastions were added, some after the conquest by the republic.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Most of these have not been restored to their original height, but do maintain their brick walls.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The citadel in the north west of the city does retain its original height.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Around the city itself many other fortresses can still be seen.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In the north east of the old city, the hexagonal gunpowder magazine, called *Kruithuis* is located close to the citadel.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is one of only a handful that still exist in the Netherlands, and was built when the city was still part of the Spanish Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is planned to become the museum of fortress 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] One of the bastions of the fortress now houses the mini museum Bastionder.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It has been dug out in a bastion of the south side.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] On the inside it shows a unique wrought iron cannon, and an older bastion that was walled in by the current one.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] On the south side of the city, the city center and walls still border the Bossche Broek, an old polder that could never be made dry.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 1995 the dyke of the Dommel broke and an enormous amount of water entered the polder.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It also flooded and blocked the main Dutch highway A2.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In order to prevent this in the future, the area was rearranged to store excess water in case of emergencies.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 2006 the area had been furnished with higher dikes and locks that allowed a controlled flooding of the polder and some adjacent areas in case of emergency.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Bossche Broek is now a 22-hectare (54-acre) nature reserve, that stretches all the way to Vught.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is connected to the Moerputten and Vlijmens Ven, with which it forms a Natura 2000 area.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Rare species in the area are the scarce large blue and the European weather loach.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Moerputten sports the Moerputten Bridge, a 600-metre (650 yard) long nineteenth century railway bridge and engineering feat.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] What is unique about the area is its close proximity to the city center.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city is also the location of the *Bolwoningen* complex, an array of fifty experimental spherical houses designed by Dries Kreijkamp.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Lutheran Church, 's-Hertogenbosch is no longer used as a church.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city has one professional football club, FC Den Bosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is the 1967 successor of the professional branches of BVV (Bossche Voetbal Vereniging) and Wilhelmina.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Both of them still exist as amateur football clubs.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] As a successor of BVV FC Den Bosch can claim the national championship of 1948.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This championship led to the construction of stadium De Vliert, which at one time had a capacity of 30,000.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Due to the less successful years that followed, the capacity is now only 8,500 visitors.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] FC Den Bosch was the first club of Dutch international player Ruud van Nistelrooy.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is more successful in field hockey.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The women's team in particular is a dominant force in the Dutch field hockey competition.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The professional basketball club Heroes Den Bosch is also very successful.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The city's rugby club is called The Dukes and dates from 1974.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is located at a very scenic location at the foot of the city walls.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Because of the limited space, the club plays on artificial turf and part of the accommodation is subterranean.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It became the national rugby champion in 2008.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] As regards events the city is host to the Rosmalen Grass Court Championships, a combined ATP Tour and WTA Tour grass court tennis event played two weeks before the Wimbledon Championships.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The World Archery Championships and World Para Archery Championship were held here in June 2019.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] During these combined World Championships two separate venues were used: the Parade and the rugby fields of The Dukes.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] All finals took place in the arena at the Parade.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Parade is a historic square surrounded by high trees, situated at the foot of the nearly seven-hundred-year-old Saint John's Cathedral in the attractive center of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Zuid-Willemsvaart runs from the Meuse just north of the city towards Maastricht via Helmond and Weert.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 's-Hertogenbosch it runs through the city proper, south east from where a bastion has been cut off from the citadel.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Because of this route it was impossible to widen it further than for ships of CEMT class II.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Therefore, the Máxima Canal of 8 km (5 miles) was dug just east of the city, creating a shortcut from the canal to the Meuse suitable for ships of CEMT class IV.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] On the remaining part of the Zuid-Willemsvaart west of the city is the industrial harbor of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is situated on the busy A2 motorway, the most important north–south connection of the Netherlands.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This connection was established with the opening of the Dieze Bridge in 1942.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] From 1961 the Utrecht-'s-Hertogenbosch section was 2 times 2 lanes.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 1970 the A2 was rerouted to the east of the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 1989 it finally became a controlled-access highway.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 1996 the section between 's-Hertogenbosch and Eindhoven became a controlled-access highway.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The situation in Maastricht was only solved in 2016, when the Koning Willem-Alexandertunnel was opened.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] On the east–west axis 's-Hertogenbosch is on the A59 motorway.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The A65 motorway between 's-Hertogenbosch and Tilburg is a regional highway, but is not completely access-controlled.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is on the Utrecht–Boxtel part of the railway stretch between Amsterdam and the Dutch industrial/tech center near Eindhoven.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] As a consequence north–south trains depart every ten minutes.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] On the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway trains run on a more modest schedule.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is also a major station for Arriva buslines that serve the city and most of its suburbs.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Other stations within the limits of the municipality are 's-Hertogenbosch Oost railway station and Rosmalen railway station.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Vught railway station is actually closer to the city center than that in Rosmalen.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has attempted to adapt to the growing popularity of the bicycle in Dutch cities.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] A reasonable amount of bike paths has so far been constructed in the town.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In 2011, the city was chosen as *Fietsstad 2011*—the top bike city of the Netherlands for 2011.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] This is a big achievement for a city where bicycle use is lower than in the rest of the Netherlands".
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has multiple vocational universities called *Hogeschool* in Dutch.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The HAS Hogeschool of about 3,500 students is focused on agricultural and food technology.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Avans Hogeschool is located in 's-Hertogenbosch and two nearby cities.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Joost is an art academy that is now part of Avans and dates back to 1812.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Fontys Hogeschool also offers some education in the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Academy of Data Science (JADS), located at the Mariënburg Campus in the center of 's-Hertogenbosch, and provides a number of data science programs at graduate (MSc) and post-graduate level (PhD).
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is a department of the Eindhoven University of Technology and Tilburg University.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] In secondary education the City Gymnasium is a gymnasium (school) that originated from the Latin school of the city.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is comparable to a grammar school and can trace its origin back 1274.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The same type of education and all other types of secondary education are offered by a number of large institutes.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Roman Catholicism is the dominant religion in 's-Hertogenbosch, with somewhat more than 40% of the population counting themselves as belonging to it.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Even so, attendance at mass is significantly lower than 40%.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Three churches in the city center are still in use by the Catholic church: Saint John's Cathedral, Saint Catherine and the Monastery Church of the Franciscans nearby the railway station.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] Smaller churches in use by the Roman Catholic church are: Saint Anne's Church in Hintham, Saint Landoline Church in Empel, Saint Willibrord Church in Maaspoort, Saint Lambert Church (Rosmalen), etc.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Protestant religion has seen its share of believers in the city fall from 20% to about 4%.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Eastern Orthodox Church is a new church in town.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] It is based at Saint Catherine's Church where Catholic worship services have been held again since 2021.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Arrahma Mosque has been built by the Moroccan community.
[src:netherlands/s-hertogenbosch] The Turkish community has the Orhan Gazi Mosque.
